# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: thomas-jefferson
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:thomas-jefferson/11-september-1922-revolution] The **11 September 1922 Revolution** (Greek: Επανάσταση της 11ης Σεπτεμβρίου 1922) was an uprising by the Greek Army and Navy against the government in Athens, which installed a "Revolutionary Committee" in its place.
[src:thomas-jefferson/11-september-1922-revolution] The uprising took place on 24 September 1922, although the date was "11 September" on the Julian calendar still in use at the time in Greece.
[src:thomas-jefferson/11-september-1922-revolution] The Greek Army had just been defeated in the Asia Minor Campaign and had been evacuated from Anatolia to the Greek islands in the eastern Aegean.
[src:thomas-jefferson/11-september-1922-revolution] Discontent among the middle-ranking officers and men for the campaign's conduct by the royal government boiled over into armed revolt led by pro-Venizelist and anti-royalist officers.
[src:thomas-jefferson/11-september-1922-revolution] The mutiny spread quickly and seized power in Athens, forcing King Constantine I to abdicate and leave the country, with a military government ruling the country until early 1924, shortly before the Greek monarchy was abolished and the Second Hellenic Republic established.
[src:thomas-jefferson/11-september-1922-revolution] The defeat of the Greek forces in Anatolia had alarmed the people and caused them to ask for the punishment of those responsible for the defeat.
[src:thomas-jefferson/11-september-1922-revolution] The government of Petros Protopapadakis resigned and on 28 August, the new government headed by Nikolaos Triantafyllakos.
[src:thomas-jefferson/11-september-1922-revolution] On 11 September a revolution was declared, with the formation of a Revolutionary Committee headed by Colonel Nikolaos Plastiras as representative of the army in Chios, Colonel Stylianos Gonatas as representative of the army in Lesvos and Commander Dimitrios Fokas as representative of the navy.
[src:thomas-jefferson/11-september-1922-revolution] The next day, the troops boarded their ships and headed to Athens.
[src:thomas-jefferson/11-september-1922-revolution] On 13 September, the ships with the Greek army arrived in Lavrio and the next day, King Constantine resigned and went into exile in Italy.
[src:thomas-jefferson/11-september-1922-revolution] On 15 September, the troops of revolution entered the city of Athens and blocked the efforts Theodoros Pangalos was making to take advantage of the situation and take control of the government.
[src:thomas-jefferson/11-september-1922-revolution] Soon a new government was formed, with Sotirios Krokidas as chairman.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] The **14 July Revolution**, also known as the **1958 Iraqi military coup**, was a military coup that took place on 14 July 1958 in Iraq, resulting in the toppling of King Faisal II and the overthrow of the Hashemite-led Kingdom of Iraq.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] The Iraqi Republic established in its wake ended the Hashemite Arab Federation between Iraq and Jordan that had been established just six months earlier.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] The Kingdom of Iraq had been a hotbed of Arab nationalism since the Second World War.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] Unrest mounted amid economic malaise and widespread disapproval of Western influence, which was exacerbated by the formation of the Baghdad Pact in 1955, as well as Faisal's support of the British-led invasion of Egypt during the Suez Crisis.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] Prime Minister Nuri al-Said's policies were unpopular, particularly within the military ranks.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] Opposition groups began to organize in secret, modelling themselves after the Egyptian Free Officers Movement that overthrew the Egyptian monarchy in 1952.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] Pan-Arabic sentiment in Iraq was further bolstered by the creation of the United Arab Republic in February 1958 under the leadership of Gamal Abdel Nasser, a staunch proponent of anti-imperialist causes.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] In July 1958, units of the Royal Iraqi Army were dispatched to Jordan in support of King Hussein.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] A group of Iraqi Free Officers, led by Brigadier Abdul-Karim Qasim and Colonel Abdul Salam Arif, took advantage of the opportunity and instead marched on Baghdad.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] On 14 July, revolutionary forces seized control of the capital and proclaimed a new republic, headed by a Revolutionary Council.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] King Faisal and Crown Prince Abd al-Ilah were executed at the royal Al-Rehab Palace, bringing an end to the Hashemite dynasty in Iraq.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] Prime Minister al-Said attempted to flee but was captured and shot a day later.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] After the coup, Qasim assumed the position of Prime Minister and Minister of Defence, while Arif was named Deputy Prime Minister and Minister of the Interior.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] A provisional constitution was adopted in late July.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] By March 1959, the new Iraqi government had withdrawn from the Baghdad Pact and aligned itself with the Soviet Union.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] During the Second World War, Iraq was home to a growing number of Arab nationalists.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] They aimed, in part, to remove British imperial influence in Iraq.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] This sentiment grew from a politicised educational system in Iraq and an increasingly assertive and educated middle class.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] The two directors of the educational system in Iraq, Sami Shawkat and Fadhil al-Jamal, employed teachers who were political refugees from Palestine and Syria.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] These exiles fled to Iraq because of their roles in anti-British and anti-French protests, and subsequently fostered Arab nationalist consciousness in their Iraqi students.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] The growing general awareness of Arab identity led to anti-imperialism.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] Similarly, Pan-Arab sentiment grew across the Arab world and was promoted by Egypt's Gamal Abdel Nasser, a rising politician and staunch opponent of imperialism.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] Hashemite Iraq faced and confronted these sentiments as well.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] Nuri al-Said, the Iraqi Prime Minister during most of the 1930s, 1940s and 1950s, was interested in pursuing the idea of a federation of Arab States of the Fertile Crescent, but was less enthusiastic about a Pan-Arab state.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] Al-Said brought Iraq into the Arab League in 1944, seeing it as a forum for bringing together the Arab states while leaving the door open for a possible future federation.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] The League's charter enshrined the principle of autonomy for each Arab state and referenced pan-Arabism only rhetorically.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] The Iraqi economy fell into a recession and then a depression following the Second World War; inflation was uncontrolled and the Iraqi standard of living fell.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] Al-Said and the Arab Nationalist regent, Abd al-Ilah, were continually in opposition to each other, failing to agree on a cohesive economic policy, infrastructure improvements, or other internal reforms.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] In 1950, al-Said persuaded the Iraqi Petroleum Company to increase the royalties paid to the Iraqi government.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] Al-Said looked to the Hashemite Kingdom of Iraq's growing oil revenues to fund and propel development.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] He determined that 70 percent of Iraq's revenue from oil was to be set aside for infrastructure development by a Development Board with three foreign advisors out of six total members.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] This foreign presence provoked popular disapproval of al-Said's policy.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] Despite anti-Western sentiments toward oil and development, al-Said hired Lord Salter, a British economist and former politician, to investigate the prospects for development in Iraq because al-Said's oil revenue reallocation seemed to be ineffective.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] Lord Salter continued to make suggestions as to how to implement development projects despite massive Iraqi dislike of his presence.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] During the Second World War, the British reoccupied Iraq.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] In 1947 prime minister Salih Jabr negotiated British withdrawal, formalised on 15 January 1948 by the Anglo-Iraqi Treaty (also known as the Portsmouth Treaty).
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] This agreement included a British and Iraqi joint defence board to oversee Iraqi military planning, and the British continued to control Iraqi foreign affairs.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] Iraq was still tied to Great Britain for military supplies and training.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] This 25-year treaty was to last until 1973—a duration that Arab nationalists in the Hashemite Kingdom of Iraq could not accept.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] As a strong reaction to the Anglo-Iraqi Treaty of 1948, Arab nationalists led the Wathbah Rebellion a year later in protest of the continued British presence in Iraq.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] Al-Said repudiated the Portsmouth Treaty to appease the rebellious Iraqi and Arab nationalists.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] In 1955, Iraq entered into the Baghdad Pact with Iran, Pakistan, and Turkey.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] The pact was a defence agreement between the four nations and was endorsed by the UK and the United States as an anti-communist Cold War strategy, but was greatly resented by Iraqis in general.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] Egypt saw the Baghdad Pact as a provocation and a challenge to its regional dominance.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] In 1956, when Egypt nationalised the Suez Canal, Iraqi-Egyptian relations were further strained.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] When British, French and Israelis invaded Egypt, Iraq, as a British ally, had to support the invasion.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] The fact that imperial ties dragged Iraq into supporting this invasion of Arab lands led to wide disapproval across the Iraqi populace, which largely sympathised with Egypt and responded to pan-Arab ideology.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] It felt that the invasion of Egypt was another sign of Western aggression and dominance in the region.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] Similarly, when Egypt and Syria united to form the United Arab Republic (UAR) under the banner of pan-Arabism in 1958, Iraqi politicians found themselves in a vulnerable position.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] Iraqi leaders had no interest in uniting with Egypt and instead proposed and ratified their own pan-Arab union with Hashemite Jordan in May 1958.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] Great Britain and the United States openly supported this union, but many Iraqis were suspicious of its purpose and regarded the Hashemite Arab Federation as another "tool of their Western overlord".
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] The primary goal of the coup was to liberate Iraq from its imperial ties with the British and the United States.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] The Western powers dominated all sectors of Iraqi governance: national politics and reform, regional politics with its Arab and non-Arab neighbours, and economic policies.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] As a general rule, many Iraqis were resentful of the presence of Western powers in the region, especially the British.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] Furthermore, Hashemite monarchic rule could not be divorced from the image of imperial masters behind the monarchy.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] The monarchy had struggled to maintain power during the Al-Wathbah uprising in 1948 and the Iraqi Intifada of 1952.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] A growing number of educated élites in the Hashemite Kingdom of Iraq were becoming enamoured with the ideals espoused by Nasser's pan-Arab movement.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] The ideas of **qawmiyah** (Nationalism) found many willing adherents, particularly within the officer classes of the Iraqi military.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] Al-Said's policies were considered anathema by certain individuals within the Iraqi armed forces, and opposition groups began to form, modelled on the Egyptian Free Officers Movement that had overthrown the Egyptian monarchy in 1952.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] Despite al-Said's efforts to quell growing unrest within the military ranks (such as economic programmes designed to benefit the officer class, and brokering deals with the U.S. to supply the Iraqi military), his position was significantly weakened by the events of the Suez Crisis.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] Al-Said suffered for his association with Britain; the latter's role in the Crisis seeming a damning indictment of his **wataniyah** policies.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] Despite al-Said's efforts to distance himself from the crisis, the damage was done to his position.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] Iraq became isolated within the Arab world, as highlighted by its exclusion from the "Treaty of Arab Solidarity" in January 1957.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] The Suez Crisis benefited Nasser's pan-Arab cause while simultaneously undermining those Arab leaders who followed pro-Western policy.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] Al-Said's policies fell firmly within the latter camp, and covert opposition to his government steadily grew in the wake of Suez.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] On 1 February 1958, Egypt and Syria boosted the pan-Arab movement immeasurably with the announcement that they had united as the United Arab Republic (UAR).
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] The move was a catalyst for a series of events that culminated in revolution in Iraq.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] The formation of the UAR and Nasser's lofty rhetoric calling for a united Arab world galvanised pan-Arabism in both the Hashemite Kingdom of Iraq and the Hashemite Kingdom of Jordan.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] Their governments attempted something of a response with the creation of the Hashemite Arab Federation on 14 February—a union of the two states—but few were impressed by this knee-jerk reaction to the UAR.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] The Mutawakkilite Kingdom of Yemen (North Yemen) joined the UAR soon after its formation.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] Attention then shifted to Lebanon, where Syria sponsored the Arab nationalist movement in its civil war campaign against the pro-Western government of Camille Chamoun.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] Al-Said recognised that Chamoun's defeat would leave Iraq and Jordan isolated.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] He bolstered Chamoun's government with aid throughout May and June 1958.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] More fatefully, he attempted to bolster Jordan with units from the Royal Iraqi Army, a move that was a direct catalyst for the *coup d'état*.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] On 14 July 1958, a group that identified as the Free Officers, a secret military group led by Brigadier Abdul-Karim Qasim, overthrew the monarchy.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] This group was markedly Pan-Arab in character.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] King Faisal II, Prince Abd al-Ilah, and Nuri al-Said were all killed.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] The Free Officers were inspired by and modelled after the Egyptian Free Officers who overthrew the Egyptian monarchy in 1952.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] They represented all parties and cut across political factions.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] Qasim was a member of the generation that had launched the revolution in Egypt, and had grown up in an era where radicalism and pan-Arabism were circulating in schools, including high schools and military academies.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] As a group, most of the Free Officers were Sunni Arabs who came from a modern middle class.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] The Free Officers were inspired by a number of events in the Middle East the decade before 1952.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] The 1948 war against Israel was an experience that intensified the Egyptian Free Officers' sense of duty.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] They understood their mission as deposing the corrupt regimes that had weakened a unified Arab nation and thrown their countries into distress.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] The success of the Free Officers in overthrowing the Egyptian monarchy and seizing power in 1952 made Nasser a source of inspiration too.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] The Iraqi Free Officer group was an underground organization, and much of the planning and timing rested in the hands of Qasim and his associate, Colonel Abdul Salam Arif.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] The Free Officers sought to ensure Nasser's support and the assistance of the UAR to implement the revolt because they feared the members of the Baghdad Pact would subsequently overthrow the Free Officers as a reaction to the coup.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] Nasser only offered moral support, whose material significance remained vague, so Egypt had no practical role in the Iraqi revolution.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] The dispatching of Iraqi army units to Jordan played into the hands of two of the key members of the Iraqi Free Officers movement: Arif and the movement's leader, Qasim.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] The Iraqi 19th and 20th Brigades of the 3rd Division (Iraq) (the former under Qasim's command and the latter including Arif's battalion) were dispatched to march to Jordan, along a route that passed Baghdad.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] The opportunity for a coup was seized upon by the conspirators.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] Arif marched on Baghdad with the 20th Brigade and seized control of the capital, with the help of Colonel Abd al-Latif al-Darraji, while Qasim remained in reserve with the 19th at Jalawla.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] In the early hours of 14 July, Arif seized control of Baghdad's broadcasting station, which was soon to become the coup's headquarters, and broadcast the first announcement of the revolution.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] Arif "denounced imperialism and the clique in office; proclaimed a new republic and the end of the old regime...announced a temporary sovereignty council of three members to assume the duties of the presidency; and promised a future election for a new president".
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] Arif then dispatched two detachments from his regiment, one to al-Rahab Palace to deal with King Faisal II and the Crown Prince 'Abd al-Ilah, the other to Nuri al-Said's residence.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] Despite the presence of the crack Royal Guard at the Palace, no resistance was offered, by order of the Crown Prince.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] It is uncertain what orders were given to the palace detachment, and what level of force they detailed.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] At approximately 8:00 am the King, Crown Prince, Princess Hiyam ('Abd al-Ilah's wife), Princess Nafeesa ('Abd al-Ilah's mother), Princess Abadiya (Faisal's aunt), other members of the Iraqi Royal Family, and several servants were killed or wounded as they were leaving the palace.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] Only Princess Hiyam survived, although how and why is unclear.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] With their demise, the Iraqi Hashemite dynasty ended.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] Meanwhile, al-Said temporarily slipped the net of his would-be captors by escaping across the Tigris after being alerted by the sound of gunfire.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] By noon, Qasim arrived in Baghdad with his forces and set up headquarters in the Ministry of Defence building.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] The conspirators' attention then shifted to finding al-Said, lest he escape and undermine the coup's early success.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] A reward of 10,000 Iraqi dinars was offered for his capture, and a large-scale search began.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] On 15 July he was spotted in a street in the al-Battawin quarter of Baghdad attempting to escape disguised in a woman's abaya.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] Al-Said and his accomplice were both shot, and his body was buried in the cemetery at Bab al-Mu'azzam later that evening.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] Mob violence continued even in the wake of al-Said's death.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] Spurred by Arif to liquidate traitors, uncontrollable mobs took to the streets of Baghdad.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] The body of 'Abd al-Ilah was taken from the palace, mutilated and dragged through the streets, and finally hanged outside the Ministry of Defence.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] Several foreign nationals, including Jordanian and American citizens, staying at the Baghdad Hotel were killed by the mob.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] A mob invaded the British embassy and set it on fire.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] The comptroller of the British ambassador's household, Colonel P.L.Graham MC, was shot dead in the embassy building and his body was never recovered.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] The Ambassador and other British embassy staff were lucky to escape with their lives.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] After taking refuge in the registry of the embassy, which the mob threatened to burn down, they were escorted to safety by the Iraqi army.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] Mass mob violence did not die down until Qasim imposed a curfew, which still did not prevent the disinterment, mutilation and parading of Al-Said's corpse through the streets the day after its burial.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] Abdul-Karim Qasim's sudden coup took the U.S. government by surprise.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] Central Intelligence Agency (CIA) Director Allen Dulles told President Dwight D.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] Eisenhower that he believed Nasser was behind it.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] Dulles also feared that a chain reaction would occur throughout the Middle East and that the governments of Iraq, Jordan, Saudi Arabia, Turkey, and Iran would be doomed.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] The Hashemite monarchy represented a reliable ally of the Western world in thwarting Soviet advances, so the coup compromised Washington's position in the Middle East.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] Indeed, the Americans saw it in epidemiological terms.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] Qasim reaped the greatest reward, being named Prime Minister and Minister of Defence.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] Arif became Deputy Prime Minister, Minister of the Interior, and deputy Commander in Chief.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] Thirteen days after the revolution, a temporary constitution was announced, pending a permanent organic law to be promulgated after a free referendum.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] According to the document, Iraq was a republic and a part of the Arab nation and the official state religion was listed as Islam.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] Both the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies were abolished.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] Powers of legislation were vested in the Council of Ministers, with the approval of the Sovereignty Council; the executive function was also vested in the Council of Ministers.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] On 9 March 1959, *The New York Times* reported that the situation in Iraq was initially "confused and unstable, with rival groups competing for control.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] The new Iraqi Republic was headed by a Revolutionary Council.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] At its head was a three-man sovereignty council, composed of members of Iraq's three main communal/ethnic groups.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] Muhammad Mahdi Kubbah represented the Shi'a population; Khalid al-Naqshabandi, the Kurds; and Najib al Rubay’i, the Sunni population.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] This tripartite council assumed the role of the presidency.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] A cabinet was created, composed of a broad spectrum of Iraqi political movements, including two National Democratic Party representatives, one member of al-Istiqlal, one Ba'ath representative and one Marxist.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] By March 1959, Iraq withdrew from the Baghdad Pact and created alliances with left-leaning countries and communist countries, including the Soviet Union.
[src:thomas-jefferson/14-july-revolution] Because of their agreement with the USSR, Qasim's government allowed the formation of an Iraqi Communist Party.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] Portions of dialogue and some lyrics were taken directly from the letters and memoirs of the actual participants of the Second Continental Congress.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] John Adams, representing Massachusetts in the Second Continental Congress in Philadelphia, laments the body's refusal to debate his motion to declare the colonies' independence from Great Britain and instead to discuss more trivial matters.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] Disliked by most of his fellow Congressmen, he frequently seeks advice and comfort from his wife, Abigail.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] Benjamin Franklin of Pennsylvania, one of the few who enjoys Adams' company due mainly to their shared dream of independence, suggests someone else propose the independence resolution.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] Richard Henry Lee of Virginia eagerly agrees, and he rides home to get authorization from the state legislature to do so.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] Lee returns, proposes the resolution and, over the objections of John Dickinson of Pennsylvania, leader of the Conservative faction seeking reconciliation with Britain, Congress agrees to debate the question, which becomes heated as tempers flare.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] Caesar Rodney of Delaware, suffering from cancer, collapses and is forced to leave during the debate, depriving Adams of Delaware's vote.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] A new delegation from New Jersey arrives and votes in favor of independence (Franklin receives word that his son William, the Royal Governor of New Jersey, has been arrested).
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] Seeking to kill the motion, Dickinson successfully moves that an independence vote be unanimous on the grounds that "no colony be torn away from its mother country without its own consent." To salvage the motion, Adams asks for a postponement to draft a declaration of grievances.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] President of the Congress, John Hancock, breaks the tie vote in favor of a declaration and appoints Adams, Franklin, Roger Sherman of Connecticut, Robert Livingston of New York, and Thomas Jefferson of Virginia to a committee to write it.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] Despite his determination to go home to his wife, Martha, Jefferson reluctantly agrees to be the primary writer.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] After a full week passes without Jefferson's being able to complete the task, Adams summons Martha to Philadelphia; Martha charms both Adams and Franklin, and Jefferson finishes the draft.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] To convince Samuel Chase of Maryland to support independence, Adams agrees to accept General George Washington's plea to visit the army encampment in New Brunswick, New Jersey, taking Franklin and Chase with him.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] After the members return to their lodgings, a young military courier arrives and sadly relates to Congressional custodian Andrew McNair how his two best friends were killed in battle at Lexington.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] After Adams and Franklin return from New Jersey, the Declaration is read to the full Congress, which begins accepting many amendments.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] Jefferson agrees to almost all of the changes, except striking language referring to King George as a "tyrant" and objecting to slavery.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] Edward Rutledge of South Carolina leads the Southern members in walking out in protest just as Chase returns with Maryland's vote supporting independence.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] Frustrated at Adams's refusal to compromise, Franklin tells him that to achieve the primary goal of independence Adams must accept that those with opinions contrary to his will be part of their new nation.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] Badly shaken, Adams again seeks counsel from Abigail, and thanks to a delivery of much-needed saltpeter from her and the delegate from Georgia's sudden decision to support independence, Adams finds the strength and will to continue.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] On the day of the vote (July 2, 1776), Adams and Jefferson agree to drop the slavery provision, and Rutledge and the other Southern states vote for independence.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] With Delaware divided, Rodney is brought back to support independence by majority vote of its three representatives.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] Eventually, all states vote for independence except divided Pennsylvania and New York, whose remaining representative, Lewis Morris, has abstained throughout the proceedings.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] When Dickinson rises to vote against the proposal, Franklin moves that the Pennsylvania delegation be polled: he votes for independence and Dickinson votes against it, leaving the question up to James Wilson.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] Not wanting to be remembered for casting the decisive vote against American independence, Wilson votes in favor.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] Dickinson resigns from Congress and vows to join the army to support the fight against the British, even though he believes it to be futile.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] As the members prepare to sign the Declaration of Independence on July 4, 1776, Morris receives word that his estates have been destroyed and his family moved to safety.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] Despite not being authorized, Morris signs anyway.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] As McNair tolls the building's bell, one member per state signs, establishing the United States of America.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] An asterisk (*) indicates an actor or actress who was also in the original Broadway cast.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] An original motion picture soundtrack album was released in 1972 by Columbia Records on vinyl LP records.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] It contains all the musical numbers, with the exception of "Cool, Cool Considerate Men" and "Compliments".
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] The soundtrack also contains the edited versions of some of the musical numbers that were presented in full on the laserdisc and DVD releases.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] Although the Original Broadway Cast recording was released on CD in 1992, the film soundtrack remains unavailable in any digital format as of 2026.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] Warner bought the film rights to the musical for $1.25 million.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] Many members of the original Broadway cast, including William Daniels, Ken Howard, John Cullum, and Howard da Silva, reprised their roles for the film.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] Ralston Hill, Ron Holgate, David Ford, Charles Rule and others repeated their roles from the Broadway production, marking their only appearances in feature film.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] This was a decision Warner made himself after feeling he made a mistake by turning down Julie Andrews for the 1964 film adaptation of *My Fair Lady* in favor of Audrey Hepburn.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] Exteriors were filmed at the Warner Ranch in Burbank, California, the former Columbia Pictures backlot, where they built an entire street of Colonial Philadelphia.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] Most of the Colonial sets were destroyed by a fire in the mid-1970s.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] The water fountain seen during the musical number "The Lees of Old Virginia", with Ben Franklin, John Adams, and Richard Henry Lee, became known to television viewers as the fountain seen during the beginning credits of the TV series *Friends*.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] This fountain still exists directly across the street from the *Bewitched* and *I Dream of Jeannie* houses.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] Interiors were shot at the old Columbia studio on Gower Street in Hollywood.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] *1776* was among the final films shot at Gower Studios before the Warner/Columbia merger in 1971.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] "Cool, Cool, Considerate Men" was cut from the film prior to its release and not included on the soundtrack recording nor on the first VHS tapes and laserdiscs.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] The *Los Angeles Times* stated "The song 'Cool, Cool, Considerate Men' depicts Revolutionary War–era conservatives as power-hungry wheedlers focused on maintaining wealth." According to Jack L.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] Warner, the film's producer and a friend of President Richard Nixon, Nixon requested the song be removed.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] Warner's attempt to comply with Nixon's demands had initially been rebuffed by director Hunt during production, only for the song to be removed in post-production while Hunt was on vacation.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] Warner also wanted the original negative of the song shredded, but the film's editor kept it in storage unaltered.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] (The footage, some of physically poor quality, was restored for the DVD and Blu-Ray releases.) Trailers had already been released in theaters with the "Considerate Men" number as its centerpiece; Warner had those trailers pulled and re-edited.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] In a 2015 interview, Hunt mentioned that Warner, on his deathbed in 1978, told a friend that he regretted editing the scene, believing he had ruined the film's structure as a result.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] It was only decades later that the song was restored to the film.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] When the Broadway musical was about to be presented to Nixon at the White House in 1970, before the film was made, his staff pressed the producers to cut the song then; their request was denied.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] Some of the dialogue was taken from words written, often years or even decades later, by the actual people involved, and rearranged for dramatic effect.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] The film particularly omits the views of the mid-Atlantic Quaker population, represented by Dickinson.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] A supposed physical fight between Dickinson and Adams is portrayed, in which Dickinson calls Adams a "lawyer" as an epithet, despite the fact that Dickinson was a lawyer himself.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] Despite the film's inclusion of Martha Jefferson and Abigail Adams, Dickinson's wife, Mary Norris Dickinson, was the only spouse actually present in Philadelphia during the convention.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] (Franklin's common-law wife, Deborah Read, had died a year or so earlier.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] Another departure from history is that the separation from Great Britain was accomplished in two steps: the actual vote for independence came on July 2 with the approval of Lee's resolution of independence.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] The wording of the Declaration of Independence—the statement to the world as to the reasons necessitating the split—was then debated for three days before being approved on July 4.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] The vote for independence did not hinge on passages being removed from the Declaration, since Congress had already voted in favor of independence.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] For the sake of drama, the play's authors combined the two events.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] In addition, some historians believe the Declaration was not signed on July 4, but on August 2, 1776.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] Others note that the final copy of the document was signed by the delegates over several weeks and months, commencing in July and not completed until as late as September.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] The Liberty Bell in *1776* is shown being rung as the delegates were signing the Declaration on July 4; however, Independence Hall's wooden steeple was structurally unstable, and the Liberty Bell was silent, having been lowered into the upper chamber of the brick tower.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] A smaller bell, used to toll the hours, may have rung on July 8, for the public reading of the Declaration.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] Many characters in *1776* differ from their historical counterparts.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] Central to the drama is the depiction of John Adams as "obnoxious and disliked." According to biographer David McCullough, Adams was one of the most respected members of Congress in 1776.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] Adams's often-quoted description of himself in Congress as "obnoxious, suspected, and unpopular" is from a letter written 46 years later in 1822, after his unpopular presidency had likely colored his view of the past.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] According to McCullough, no delegate described Adams as obnoxious in 1776.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] Historian Garry Wills earlier made a similar argument, writing that "historians relay John Adams's memories without sufficient skepticism", and that it was Dickinson, not Adams, who was advocating an unpopular position in 1776.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] The Committee of Five appointed to write the Declaration of Independence were: Franklin, age 70 (Howard da Silva was 62 at the time of filming in 1971); Roger Sherman, 55 (Rex Robbins was 36); Adams, 41 (Daniels was 44); Jefferson, 33 (Ken Howard was 27); and Livingston, 29 (John Myhers was 49).
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] Adams" say Livingston claims to have "been presented with a new son by the noble stork" to avoid writing the declaration; no such son ever existed.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] For practical and dramatic purposes, only 20 of the over 50 members of Congress present at the time are portrayed.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] This version of John Adams is, in part, a composite character, combining the real Adams with his cousin Samuel Adams, who was in Congress at the time but is mentioned as being absent in the script.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] Although the play depicts Delaware's Caesar Rodney as an elderly man near death from skin cancer (which would eventually kill him), he was just 47 years old at the time and continued to be very active in the Revolution after signing the Declaration.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] He was not absent from the voting because of health; however, the play is accurate in having him arrive "in the nick of time", having ridden 80 miles (130 km) the night before (an event depicted on Delaware's 1999 State Quarter) unaided, instead of with the help of another delegate.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] Further, Richard Henry Lee announces that he is returning to Virginia to serve as governor.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] He was never governor (it was Lee's ally Patrick Henry who assumed the post at that time); his cousin Henry Lee (who is anachronistically called "General 'Lighthorse' Harry Lee", a rank and nickname earned later) did eventually become governor (and the father of Confederate general Robert E.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] John Adams was also depicted as disliking Richard Henry Lee, but according to McCullough, Adams expressed nothing but "respect and admiration for the tall, masterly Virginian." He did dislike Benjamin Franklin, contrary to what was portrayed.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] Martha Jefferson never traveled to Philadelphia to be with her husband; she was extremely ill during the summer of 1776, having just endured a miscarriage.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] The play's authors invented the scene "to show something of the young Jefferson's life without destroying the unity of setting." Martha is also depicted as dancing a galop or polka with Franklin and Adams, dances not introduced until the 1800s.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] The real Martha Jefferson would have been seated playing the early piano Thomas purchased for her, accompanying him as he played violin.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] The film, like its stage counterpart, misidentifies John Morton, the deciding vote and a soft-spoken judge who only votes for the resolution to avoid being infamous for killing it, as James Wilson.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] The real Wilson, though he had previously studied under Dickinson earlier in his career, had by 1776 become one of the most outspoken advocates for independence, and would only later become a judge on the Supreme Court.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] His patrician WASP accent in the film is misleading, since Wilson was a Scottish immigrant whose parents were farmers, while Morton's family was from Finland.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] The quote attributed to Edmund Burke by Dr.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] Lyman Hall in a key scene with Adams is a paraphrase of a real quote by Burke.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] The song "Cool Considerate Men" is anachronistic; the terms "right" and "left" in politics were not in use until the French Revolution of 1789.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] John Dickinson, who is portrayed as an antagonist here, was motivated mainly by his Quaker roots and his respect for the British Constitution, having lived in England for 3 years in the 1750s.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] He was no wealthier than some members of the pro-Independence faction, and freed his slaves in 1777.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] Thomas Jefferson wrote that "his name will be consecrated in history as one of the great worthies of the revolution".
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] The film also misses the objection some had to the Declaration's stated basis in "rights of Man" based in "natural law" derived from a supernatural being.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] The Quaker-based population in the mid-Atlantic, represented by Dickinson, objected to this conception.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] The musical also deviates from history in its portrayal of attitudes about slavery.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] In *1776*, after a dramatic debate over slavery, the southern delegates walk out in protest of the Declaration's denunciation of the slave trade, and only support independence when that language was removed from the Declaration.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] The walkout is fictional, as the debate over the wording of the declaration took place after the vote for independence on July 2, and apparently most delegates, northern and southern, supported the deletion of the clause.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] The musical depicts Edward Rutledge as the leader of the opposition to an anti-slavery clause in Jefferson's original draft of the Declaration.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] However, while it is known that, according to Jefferson, the clause was opposed by South Carolina and Georgia, plus unspecified "northern brethren", that is all that is known about opposition to the clause.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] Rutledge was a delegate from South Carolina, but there is no historical evidence that he played any part—much less a leadership role—in the opposition to the clause.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] The musical does acknowledge the complexity of the Colonial attitudes toward slavery in the dramatic song "Molasses to Rum," sung by the Rutledge character, which illustrates the hypocrisy in northern condemnations of slavery since northerners profited from the triangle trade.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] The musical depicts Franklin as claiming that he is the founder of the first abolitionist organization in the New World; the real Franklin did not become an abolitionist until after the American Revolution, becoming president of the Pennsylvania Abolition Society in 1785.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] It was actually Dickinson who freed his slaves in 1776, conditionally at first, and fully by 1787 when the Constitution was ratified.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] In both the play and the film, John Adams sarcastically predicts that Benjamin Franklin will receive from posterity too great a share of credit for the Revolution.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] "Franklin smote the ground and out sprang—George Washington.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] James Wilson is portrayed as subordinating himself to Dickinson's opposition to independence, only changing his vote so that he would not be remembered unfavorably.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] In fact, Wilson was considered one of the leading thinkers behind the American cause, consistently supporting and arguing for independence, although he would not cast his vote until his district had been caucused.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] The formula John Adams gives Abigail for making saltpeter—"By treating sodium nitrate with potassium chloride, of course!"—refers to various chemicals by their modern names, instead of the names used in the 1770s.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] A more historically accurate version might be "treating soda niter with potash." More accurate still would have been a detailed description of the process, involving ingredients such as manure or bat guano, but that probably would have been too long, and repulsive to audiences.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] Abigail's request for pins in exchange is not frivolous.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] Electroplating had not been invented yet: The common pin was subject to rusting and breakage, and so required replacement.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] At the time, pins were necessary for a wide range of crafts, creating garments and headgear (including wigs), making lace, ribbon and other trimmings and textiles.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] They also served the roles now played by paperclips and staples.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] Women used them as closures or to anchor pieces of clothing.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] (Hooks and eyes existed, but like so many manufactured goods, they had to be imported.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] The hook-and-eye industry was not established in the United States until the early 19th century.) The real Abigail, if dressed as in this scene in the film, would have supported the front lacing of her gown by using pins to fasten the fabric to the stiffened bodice beneath.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] Vincent Canby of *The New York Times* observed, "The music is resolutely unmemorable.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] The lyrics sound as if they'd been written by someone high on root beer, and the book is familiar history—compressed here, stretched there—that has been gagged up and paced to Broadway's not-inspiring standards.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] Hunt's screen version of *1776* ... insists on being so entertaining and, at times, even moving, that you might as well stop resisting it.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] I've seen *1776* now four times and it may well be that the repetition has worn grey my true-blue patriotism.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] The movie is a good technical copy but rather than adding to the original in any meaningful way it merely fills it out with the usual superfluity of second-hand screen work.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] Peter Hunt has directed with a view to maximum expenditure of energy.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] There is absolutely no chance that anyone will go to sleep during *1776*.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] Most of the actors were brought to the film from the hugely successful stage version and they all know how to milk a scene for full value." Carole Kass of the *Richmond Times-Dispatch* stated that "the film, even though the conclusion is historical knowledge, is still suspenseful.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] One cares very much about the individual delegates and their votes, opting from the theater seat for freedom.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] The film is also a reminder that when it came to pitting the status quo against progress, Virginia was one of the first to vote for tomorrow.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] In Philadelphia, the film opened to significantly different reactions across two of its daily newspapers.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] Collins of *The Philadelphia Inquirer* called the film "an affront because it trivializes a big subject without any redeeming satirical intent.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] The Founding Fathers are not cut down to human size, they are reduced to subhuman dimensions.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] They are made into singing clowns whose boobish behavior somehow produces one of the most eloquent expressions of the human spirit ever to come from the hand of man." On the other hand, Joe Baltake of the *Philadelphia Daily News* called it "a pompous, roguish, disarmingly charming movie musical.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] Its original freshness is retained largely because its 1969 Broadway ancestor never attained the household-word popularity of, say, *My Fair Lady* and *The Sound of Music*.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] Its storyline still comes across as something delightfully novel, as does its spirited score.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] Unlike other stage-to-screen adaptations, this 'new' entertainment is free of the usual telltale staleness. [...] Under director Peter Hunt's guidance, the off-beat material works surprisingly well in musical form.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] A heavy hand could have been disastrous.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] In fact, even with Hunt's light touch, "1776" occasionally gives way to a sluggish stuffiness.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] Some forbearance is necessary for total enjoyment.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] Sherman Edwards' unusual songs remain the work's high point, especially "The Egg," "He Plays His Violin," "Sit Down, John" and the haunting "Momma, Look Sharp." Technically, the film is visually enchanting—a giant kaleidoscope of sprawling sets, period costumes and gobs of color.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] The production design is equalled only by the admirable ensemble acting.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] The film got similarly mixed reviews in Chicago.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] Roger Ebert of the *Chicago Sun-Times* gave *1776* two stars and declared, "This is an insult to the real men who were Adams, Jefferson, Franklin and the rest ...
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] The performances trapped inside these roles, as you might expect, are fairly dreadful.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] There are good actors in the movie (especially William Daniels as Adams and Donald Madden as John Dickinson), but they're forced to strut and posture so much that you wonder if they ever scratched or spit or anything ...
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] I can hardly bear to remember the songs, much less discuss them.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] The movie received generally positive reviews in the United Kingdom.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] Alexander Walker of the *Evening Standard* said "it ought to be heavy going and yet the surprising thing is I didn't find it so.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] The energy is infectious." He also stated that "since it was written Into the record, *1776* could hardly ignore the moment when the reference to the slave trade was shamefully, but conveniently, struck out of the Declaration of Independence in order to carry the vote.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] Adams—a fine role for William Daniels." It was not without its detractors in England, however.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] I only wish I could say this fidelity to the original concept actually worked, but the fact is you have to keep pinching yourself to remember that you're watching movie.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] On Rotten Tomatoes, the film has a 68% score, based on 19 reviews, with an average rating of 7.1/10.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] The film was the Christmas attraction at Radio City Music Hall in New York City and performed very well, grossing $1,743,978 in its first six weeks.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] It did not perform as well in its other opening engagements in Philadelphia, Boston and Washington.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] It returned to the Music Hall for two weeks starting June 3, 1976 in honor of the United States Bicentennial.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] The film was nominated for the Golden Globe Award for Best Motion Picture – Musical or Comedy but lost to *Cabaret*.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] Harry Stradling Jr. was nominated for the Academy Award for Best Cinematography but lost to Geoffrey Unsworth for *Cabaret*.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] The film was first released on videocassette, which runs 148 minutes, and on Laserdisc in the 1980s.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] The Laserdisc version runs 180 minutes and is rated PG.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] The DVD, issued in 2002 as a "Restored Director's Cut", runs 165 minutes.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] It trims up some scenes and contains previously unreleased scenes, including the "Cool, Cool Considerate Men" musical number and accompanying dialogue.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] However, it excludes the previously released Overture (heard on laserdisc but not in cinemas).
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] The film was released on Blu-ray from a 4K-master on June 2, 2015.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] It contains two commentaries: an all-new commentary, with director Hunt, Daniels and Howard, and also the DVD commentary with Hunt and Peter Stone only.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] With two versions: the prior "Director's Cut", and a further "extended cut" (167 minutes), the release also includes two deleted and alternative scenes with filmmaker commentary, screen tests, and original theatrical trailers.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-film] On May 31, 2022, Sony Pictures released a three-disc 50th anniversary Blu-ray.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] In 1972, it was made into a film adaptation, with eight of the original Broadway actors reprising their roles.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] It has received three New York revivals: on Broadway in 1997, an Encores! concert in 2016, and a 2022 Broadway production in which the racially diverse cast was entirely made up of people who identify as female, trans, or non-binary.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] In 1925, Rodgers and Hart wrote a Broadway musical about the American Revolution called *Dearest Enemy*.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] In 1950, another musical about the Revolution was presented on Broadway, titled *Arms and the Girl*, with music by Morton Gould, lyrics by Dorothy Fields, and book by Herbert Fields, Dorothy Fields and Rouben Mamoulian, the show's director.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] Sherman Edwards, a jazz pianist and Brill Building pop songwriter who had decades prior had minor roles in Broadway musicals, began developing lyrics and libretto for a musical based on the signing of the Declaration of Independence.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] Edwards recounted that "I wanted to show [the founding fathers] at their outermost limits.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] These men were the cream of their colonies. ...
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] They disagreed and fought with each other.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] The first songs in the project were published and copyrighted by 1964.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] Producer Stuart Ostrow recommended that librettist Peter Stone collaborate with Edwards on the book of the musical.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] Adams, the outspoken delegate from Massachusetts, was chosen as the central character, and his quest to persuade all 13 colonies to vote for independence became the central conflict.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] Stone confined nearly all of the action to Independence Hall and the debate among the delegates, and featuring two female characters, Abigail Adams and Martha Jefferson, in the musical.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] After tryouts in New Haven, Conn., and Washington, D.C., the show opened on Broadway at the 46th Street Theatre on March 16, 1969.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] On May 8, 1776, the Second Continental Congress, convening in Philadelphia at present-day Independence Hall, proceeds with its business.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] John Adams, the controversial delegate from Braintree, Massachusetts, is frustrated because Congress will not even debate his proposals on independence.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] Later, Adams meets delegate Benjamin Franklin, an elderly lecherous scamp, who suggests that Adams should let another, more popular delegate propose a resolution on independence and summons the charismatic Richard Henry Lee of Stratford, Virginia.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] Lee eagerly agrees to return to Virginia to procure an independence resolution from the Virginia House of Burgesses using his family's reputation and clout ("The Lees of Old Virginia").
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] As Congress is assembled, President John Hancock notes that the entire New Jersey delegation has been absent for quite some time.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] A gloomy dispatch from George Washington, commander of the Continental Army, arrives by courier and is read aloud by Secretary Charles Thomson.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] Shortly thereafter, Richard Henry Lee returns, bearing a resolution for independence.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] Elated, Adams seconds the motion to open debate on the resolution.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] John Dickinson of Pennsylvania, a conservative and royal apologist, immediately moves to table the debate.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] The vote is close, but debate is ultimately approved, prompting Dickinson to denounce the desire for independence as an overreaction to petty squabbles with Great Britain.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] The debate becomes more heated and personal, sparking a physical fight between Dickinson and Adams and causing Caesar Rodney to intervene; Rodney collapses from cancer.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] Pro-independence Scotsman Thomas McKean escorts Rodney back to Delaware, leaving conservative George Read in control of Delaware's delegation.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] Read quickly seconds Rutledge's motion to end the debate and vote on independence, knowing it is likely to fail.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] At this moment, the Reverend John Witherspoon arrives, announcing that New Jersey's legislature has deposed its royal governor, Franklin's estranged loyalist son, and has sent Witherspoon as the new delegate with explicit instruction to vote for independence.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] Adams, now seeing a path to victory, pushes to proceed with the vote, since ties are broken by Hancock, an Adams ally who is also from Massachusetts.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] Dickinson moves to require the vote for independence to be unanimous.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] The vote ends in a tie, but Hancock unexpectedly votes in favor of unanimity, explaining that if the colonies are divided, the crown will pit the colonies against each other.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] Knowing that Dickinson will quash the resolution if the vote proceeds immediately, Adams moves to postpone the vote to buy time to rally the needed support; he proposes that Congress draft a Declaration of Independence to build support abroad for the cause.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] Again, the vote ties; this time, Hancock votes to postpone.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] Before they adjourn, John Hancock appoints a committee of Adams, Franklin, Roger Sherman of Connecticut, Robert Livingston of New York, and Lee to draft the declaration.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] Lee informs the Congress that he has been appointed Governor of Virginia and departs, never to be seen again; Adams nominates another Virginian, the resident meteorologist Thomas Jefferson, who wants no part of the task as he is returning home to see his wife after six months.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] Jefferson is forced to accept the task after the other four explain why they cannot or should not ("But, Mr.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] Adams sends for Jefferson's beloved wife Martha, reasoning that if Thomas cannot return to her, she can be summoned to him and potentially break his writer's block.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] When she arrives, she refuses to speak to Adams or Franklin and spends the night with her husband.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] Adams, alone, again exchanges letters with his wife Abigail ("Yours, Yours, Yours").
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] The next morning, Franklin and Adams again attempt to engage Martha in conversation; she speaks, but tersely, and talks of her courtship with Thomas ("He Plays the Violin").
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] Adams is delighted to find that Jefferson has written something, but instead of work on the declaration, it is a mere note asking for him and Martha to be left alone.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] In June, with the Congress in what looks like a state of total lethargy, another grim dispatch from General Washington arrives, denouncing the Continental Army recruits as useless, undisciplined and outmatched, having fallen prey to numerous prostitutes at the camp in New Brunswick, New Jersey.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] Adams, sensing that Washington is exaggerating the crisis in hopes of securing more money, convinces Samuel Chase of Maryland to go with him to New Brunswick to test Chase's fears that the Revolutionary War is doomed to end in defeat; Franklin, eager to see the prostitutes for himself, tags along.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] The conservatives depart, leaving McNair, the courier (a Continental Army corporal from Watertown, Massachusetts), and a teenage "leather apron" (workman) alone in the chamber.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] As McNair begins a mock session as *president pro tempore*, he escorts the courier to Adams's seat; there, the courier and McNair discourage the leather apron from joining the Army as the courier recalls his friends' deaths at Lexington ("Momma Look Sharp").
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] As Congress reconvenes in Philadelphia, Jefferson is outside the chamber while Thomson reads the completed draft of the declaration to the Congress.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] Adams and Franklin arrive, delighted: though the troops are indeed undisciplined, they showed exceptional shooting skill hunting waterfowl for dinner, and this convinced Chase to vote for independence.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] They congratulate Jefferson on his work, and Franklin compares the creation of this new country to the hatching of a bird, though they disagree on what kind ("The Egg").
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] On June 28, Hancock asks if there are any alterations to be offered to the Declaration of Independence.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] Many delegates voice suggestions, additions or deletions.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] Edward Rutledge of South Carolina objects in particular to a clause condemning the slave trade.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] Rutledge leads a walk-out with the delegates from both Carolinas and Georgia, and the rest of the Congress follows.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] Adams, who insists on including the slavery clause on principle that excluding it would make the Congress hypocrites, discusses the matter with Franklin, who tells Adams that he must accept some degree of compromise if he wants the independence resolution to pass.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] Adams calls on Abigail in his mind to help him, and she reminds him of his commitment to the cause ("Compliments").
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] Bolstered by her (and the arrival of a delivery of kegs of saltpeter he had previously requested from her), Adams recovers his energy and sends Franklin to try and win the support of Pennsylvania's James Wilson and Jefferson to talk to Rutledge.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] Re-reading a dispatch from Washington, Adams, now alone, wonders "Is Anybody There?" Hall returns; after considering the words of Edmund Burke, he decides to buck his constituency's loyalist preference and use his own judgment to vote Yea for independence on Georgia's behalf.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] Hancock calls for the vote on the Lee Resolution.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] At this moment, Rodney returns to Congress to assure that Delaware will vote in favor of independence.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] Although Pennsylvania passes on their first call, the rest of the New England and Mid-Atlantic colonies vote in favor of independence except for New York, who reluctantly abstains.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] South Carolina, North Carolina and Georgia all vote "yea".
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] On Pennsylvania's second call, Dickinson is about to announce that his colony votes "nay" when Franklin requests that the delegation be polled.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] Hancock proposes that no man be allowed to sit in Congress without signing the Declaration.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] Dickinson resigns but pledges his loyalty to the new nation and says he will join the army and fight on its behalf, even as he hopes for eventual reconciliation with England.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] Adams leads the Congress in a salute to Dickinson as he leaves the chamber.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] The courier arrives with another dispatch from General Washington; on the eve of the British army's looming attack on New York, Washington remarks on the bravery of his outmatched band of misfit militia members.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] Washington also notes that Lewis Morris's family estate has been completely destroyed but that the Morris family was rescued and his sons joined the Continental Army.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] Morris, in response, announces "To hell with New York" and agrees to sign the Declaration.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] On July 4, McNair is sent to ring the Liberty Bell.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] It is heard ringing in the background as Thomson calls one delegate from each colony to sign the Declaration, establishing the United States of America.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] The delegates freeze in position as the Liberty Bell rings to a fevered pitch.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] After out-of-town tryouts, the original Broadway production opened on Broadway on March 16, 1969, at the 46th Street Theatre (now the Richard Rodgers Theatre) and closed on February 13, 1972, after 1,217 performances.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] In its three-year run, it played in three different theatres: the 46th Street, the St.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] James Theatre (1970) and, finally, the Majestic Theatre (1971).
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] The principal cast included William Daniels, Howard da Silva, Paul Hecht, Clifford David, Ronald Holgate, David Ford, Virginia Vestoff and Ken Howard.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] Rex Everhart, who was da Silva's understudy, replaced him on the original Broadway cast album after da Silva suffered a mild heart attack, which required him to leave the show temporarily.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] Betty Buckley made her Broadway debut as Martha Jefferson in the original stage production.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] Clifford David left the production soon after opening.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] He was replaced as Rutledge by David Cryer who was in turn replaced by John Cullum who became one of the few Broadway replacements in history to recreate a role on film.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] The musical toured for two years in the United States and was given a London production, opening on June 16, 1970, at the New Theatre.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] The production starred Lewis Fiander as Adams, Vivienne Ross as Abigail Adams, Ronald Radd, Bernard Lloyd, David Kernan as Rutledge, John Quentin as Jefferson and Cheryl Kennedy as Martha Jefferson.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] An Australian production, also with Lewis Fiander, opened at Her Majesty's Theatre in Melbourne on 26 June 1971 and moved to the Theatre Royal in Sydney on 11 September 1971.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] City Center staged concert from March 30 to April 3, 2016.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] The cast included MacIntyre Dixon, Ric Stoneback, and Kevin Ligon reprising their roles from the 1997 revival as Andrew McNair, Samuel Chase, and George Read respectively.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] The production notably sported a racially diverse cast in light of the recent success of another musical about the Founding Fathers, *Hamilton*.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] The musical was produced in Chicago, Illinois by Porchlight Music Theatre as part of their "Porchlight Revisits" series in November 2018.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] Directed by Michael Weber, Music Directed by Jeremy Ramey, with Musical Staging by Michelle Lauto.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] The team held a two-week workshop on Zoom in April 2020, but the production was postponed due to the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] In June 2021, A.R.T. announced that the production, now directed by Jeffrey L.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] Page and Paulus, would begin performances at A.R.T. in May 2022.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] The cast (many of whom were making their Broadway debuts) included Crystal Lucas-Perry (later Kristolyn Lloyd) as Adams, Patrena Murray as Franklin, Elizabeth A.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] Davis as Jefferson, Allison Kaye Daniel as Abigail/Rev.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] Hall, Carolee Carmello as Dickinson and Sara Porkalob as Rutledge.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] A two-part radio production adapted and directed by Martin Jarvis starring Alfred Molina as Benjamin Franklin, Ioan Gruffud as John Adams.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] The musical was performed in April 2026 at the Paper Mill Playhouse in Millburn, New Jersey under the direction of Mark S.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] Hoebee with musical staging by Nancy Renée Braun.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] The cast starred Will Blum as John Adams, Michael Burrell as Thomas Jefferson, and John Treacy Egan as Benjamin Franklin.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] In the 2022 revival, the end of Act I is moved to after "He Plays the Violin".
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] According to Peter Stone, Scene Three of *1776* holds the record for the longest time in a musical without a single note of music played or sung —– over thirty minutes pass between "The Lees of Old Virginia" and "But Mr.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] On the DVD commentary, Stone says that he experimented with adding various songs in this section, but nothing ever worked.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] During this scene, dubbed "Big Three" by cast members, musicians were allowed to leave the pit, reportedly the first time in Broadway history that they were permitted to do so in the middle of a show.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] Stone also notes that people often told him that, because of the subject matter and the large amount of dialogue, *1776* should have been a conventional play rather than a musical.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] Stone believes that the songs create a playful, irreverent tone that helps bring the historical characters to life.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] The central departure from history is that the separation from Great Britain was accomplished in two steps: the actual vote for independence came on July 2 with the approval of Lee's resolution of independence.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] The vote for independence did not hinge on some passages being removed from the Declaration, as implied in the play, since Congress had already voted in favor of independence before debating the Declaration.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] In addition, some historians believe that the Declaration was not signed on July 4, as shown in *1776*, but was instead signed on August 2, 1776.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] The authors of *1776* had the delegates sign the Declaration on July 4 for dramatic reasons.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] The pro-slavery and anti-black views espoused by Rutledge in the play bear similarities to his record, though Rutledge had supported the Lee Resolution and led the campaign to convince the other South Carolina delegates to support it.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] Of the four principal characters, the musical also notably focuses on Jefferson's wife, Martha, and Adams' wife, Abigail, but omits Dickinson's wife, Mary Norris, who was actually in Philadelphia, unlike the other wives, and was an active correspondent with the other Founding Fathers.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] Franklin's common-law wife, Deborah Read, was deceased at this point.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] Adams's memories near the end of his life were, according to McCullough, likely distorted and affected by his troubled tenure as President in the late 1790s; no delegate described Adams as obnoxious in 1776.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] For practical and dramatic purposes, the play depicts only 19 of the more than 50 members of Congress who were present at the time.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] The John Adams of the play is, in part, a composite character, combining the real Adams with his cousin Samuel Adams, who is noted in the play as being absent.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] Although the play depicts Caesar Rodney as an elderly man near death from skin cancer (which would eventually kill him), he was just 47 at the time and continued to be very active in the Revolution after signing the Declaration.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] He was not absent from the voting because of health; however, the play is accurate in having him arrive "in the nick of time", having ridden 80 miles the night before (an event depicted on Delaware's 1999 State Quarter).
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] Richard Henry Lee did not leave Congress to serve as Governor of Virginia, a post assumed at the time by Patrick Henry.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] In real life, he and his brother Francis were present to sign the Declaration, and his cousin "Light-Horse Harry" Lee, mentioned in "The Lees of Old Virginia" as a general, had only reached the rank of captain by 1776.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] Adams had more admiration for the "tall, masterly Virginian" Lee than the play initially implies.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] Martha Jefferson never traveled to Philadelphia to be with her husband.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] In fact, she was extremely ill during the summer of 1776, having just endured a miscarriage.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] Jefferson rushed his work on the Declaration so he could return to Martha as soon as he could, and did so no later than August 1776, nine months before the birth of their short-lived son.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] The song "Cool Considerate Men" is anachronistic, not only because of its quotation of the not-yet-written "The Star-Spangled Banner," but because the terms "right" and "left" in politics were not in use until the French Revolution of 1789.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] Dickinson, who refused to sign the Declaration based on "rights of man" and "natural law", was seeking to avoid reopening issues from the English Civil Wars, including Oliver Cromwell's Puritan regime, and the Jacobitism cause.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] In 1689, these issues had been definitively resolved in the Glorious Revolution and the constitutionalization of the English Bill of Rights based in "rights and responsibilities of person"; the word "man" is not used except in the context of treason.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] The last Jacobite rebellion, seeking to re-establish Catholicism and the religious concept of "natural law", had only just happened in 1745, however.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] None of this background of Dickinson's position is depicted.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] Joseph Hewes is portrayed as having little to contribute to the debates, only to consistently yield to, and vote with, Rutledge.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] According to Adams's recollections several decades later, Hewes in fact was staunchly against independence but eventually and reluctantly conceded to popular support once reconciliation appeared to be impossible.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] Thomas Jefferson is depicted as saying that he has resolved to free his slaves, something he did not do, except for a few slaves freed after his death 50 years later, due to the massive debt his estate incurred and the need to keep them on the books as collateral.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] Many of Jefferson's slaves, particularly the Hemings family, were related by blood to Martha (and, after Martha's death, Jefferson is believed to have fathered others); he fought to keep the family united and treated them with privileges rare for slaves of the era.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] Franklin claims that he is the founder of an abolitionist organization (the Pennsylvania Abolition Society); however, he had only joined said society in 1785, nine years after the declaration.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] The musical misidentifies John Morton, the soft-spoken, experienced judge who cast the deciding vote in favor of independence solely to avoid the infamy of being the single vote that vetoed it, as James Wilson.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] Wilson had been cautious about supporting independence at an earlier date, but he supported the resolution of independence when it came up for a vote.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] Wilson was in fact one of the most outspoken political leaders of his era, as records tied to the later Constitutional Convention show, and would only become a judge after said Constitution was adopted.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] The desire to not singlehandedly block the independence resolution was a joint decision of all the Pennsylvania delegates; in real life, Dickinson and another delegate agreed not to attend the July 2 vote to allow Franklin, Wilson and Morton to vote yes on Pennsylvania's behalf.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] The phrase "We are about to brave the storm in a skiff made of paper", placed in the mouth of John Hancock, was actually stated by John Dickinson ("Others strenuously assert...we ought to brave the Storm in a Skiff made of Paper.") in his arguments against independence.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] Franklin's comments about the eagle and the turkey in "The Egg" were based on comments he had made in a 1784 letter he had written criticizing the Society of the Cincinnati for, among other perceived wrongs, using an eagle as a symbol.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] Furthermore, it was not Adams who chose the eagle as the *de facto* national bird, but instead secretary Charles Thomson.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] The 2022 revival production includes an excerpt of Abigail Adams' March 1776 letter to John Adams, known for its "remember the ladies" statement for women's rights.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] The 1972 film version of *1776* was produced by Jack L.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] Warner with Hunt again directing and Stone writing the screenplay.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] The film featured William Daniels as Adams, Ken Howard as Jefferson, Howard da Silva as Franklin, John Cullum as Edward Rutledge, Ron Holgate as Richard Henry Lee, and Virginia Vestoff as Abigail Adams, all of whom had performed their roles on Broadway.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] The supporting cast was also mostly recruited from the Broadway production.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] The principal exceptions were Donald Madden and Blythe Danner, who took over the roles of John Dickinson and Martha Jefferson.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] A Director's Cut of the original film has been released on DVD and Blu-ray.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] Both the look and sound of the original film have been improved through modern technology.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] Many cuts to the original film by the producer Jack Warner have been restored, including verses from the songs "Piddle Twiddle and Resolve" and "He Plays the Violin" and the entire "Cool, Cool, Considerate Men,” which Warner originally cut at the urging of President Nixon.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] Nixon felt the scene presented conservatism in a negative light.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] Musical underscoring has been removed from several scenes without songs in order to strengthen the focus on dialogue.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] Bonus material includes commentary by Director Peter Hunt and by Peter Stone, the book/screenwriter.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] Among other topics, they discuss artistic liberties and anachronisms used to dramatize the events.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1776-musical] The musical *Hamilton* references the song "Sit Down, John!" in a lyric from the song, "The Adams Administration", in the lyric: "Sit down, John, you fat mother—[BLEEP]er." Lin-Manuel Miranda discovered the *1776* film in college and cites it as having paved the way for *Hamilton*.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election] A gubernatorial election was held in Virginia on June 1, 1779.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The delegate from Albemarle County Thomas Jefferson defeated the president of the Council of State John Page.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The incumbent governor of Virginia Patrick Henry was ineligible for re-election due to term limits established by the Constitution of Virginia.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The election was conducted by the Virginia General Assembly in joint session.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election] No candidate had a majority after the first count, requiring a second ballot between the two top-finishers.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1780-virginia-gubernatorial-election] A gubernatorial election was held in Virginia on June 2, 1780.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1780-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The incumbent governor of Virginia Thomas Jefferson was re-elected.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1780-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The Senate and the House of Delegates met separately on June 1 to nominate candidates for governor; more than one nomination was made, requiring a vote of the Virginia General Assembly.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1780-virginia-gubernatorial-election] When the Assembly met in joint session the following day, Jefferson was selected by the majority of members on the first ballot, although the names of the other candidates and the votes tallied were not recorded.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Presidential elections were held in the United States from November 2 to December 5, 1792.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Incumbent President George Washington was elected to a second term by a unanimous vote in the electoral college, while John Adams was reelected as vice president.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Washington was essentially unopposed, but Adams faced a competitive re-election against Governor George Clinton of New York.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Electoral rules of the time required each presidential elector to cast two votes without distinguishing which was for president and which for vice president.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The recipient of the most votes would then become president, and the runner-up vice president.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic-Republican Party, which had organized in opposition to the policies of Secretary of the Treasury Alexander Hamilton, supported Clinton for the position of vice president.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Adams, meanwhile, was backed by the Federalist Party in his bid for another term.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Neither party had fully organized, and partisan divisions had not yet solidified.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Washington received 132 electoral votes, one from each elector.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Adams won 77 electoral votes, enough to win re-election.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Clinton finished in third place with 50 electoral votes, taking his home state of New York as well as three Southern states.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Two other candidates won the five remaining electoral votes.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1792-united-states-presidential-election] This election was the first in which each of the original 13 states appointed electors, as did the newly added states of Kentucky and Vermont.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1792-united-states-presidential-election] In 1792, presidential elections were still conducted according to the original method established under the U.S.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Under this system, each elector cast two votes: the candidate who received the greatest number of votes (so long as they won a majority) became president, while the runner-up became vice president.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The Twelfth Amendment would eventually replace this system, requiring electors to cast one vote for president and one vote for vice president, but this change did not take effect until 1804.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Because of this, it is difficult to use modern-day terminology to describe the relationship among the candidates in this election.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Washington is generally held by historians to have run unopposed.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Indeed, the incumbent president enjoyed bipartisan support and received one vote from every elector.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The choice for vice president was more divisive.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalist Party threw its support behind the incumbent vice president, John Adams of Massachusetts, while the Democratic-Republican Party backed the candidacy of New York Governor George Clinton.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Because few doubted that Washington would receive the greatest number of votes, Adams and Clinton were effectively competing for the vice presidency; under the letter of the law, however, they were technically candidates for president competing against Washington.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Born out of the Anti-Federalist faction that had opposed the Constitution in 1788, the Democratic-Republican Party was the main opposition to the agenda of Treasury Secretary Alexander Hamilton.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1792-united-states-presidential-election] They had no chance of unseating Washington, but hoped to win the vice presidency by defeating the incumbent, Adams.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Many Democratic-Republicans would have preferred to nominate Thomas Jefferson, their ideological leader and Washington's Secretary of State.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1792-united-states-presidential-election] However, this would have cost them the state of Virginia, as electors were not permitted to vote for two candidates from their home state and Washington was also a Virginian.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Clinton, the Governor of New York and a former anti-Federalist leader, became the party's nominee after he won the backing of Jefferson and James Madison.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Clinton was from an electorally important swing state, and he convinced party leaders that he would be a stronger candidate than another New Yorker, Senator Aaron Burr.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1792-united-states-presidential-election] A group of Democratic-Republican leaders met in Philadelphia in October 1792 and selected Clinton as the party's vice presidential candidate.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Madison was at first a Federalist until he opposed the establishment of Hamilton's First Bank of the United States in 1791.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1792-united-states-presidential-election] He formed the Democratic-Republican Party along with Anti-Federalist Thomas Jefferson in 1792.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The elections of 1792 were the first ones in the United States to be contested on anything resembling a partisan basis.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1792-united-states-presidential-election] In most states, the congressional elections were recognized in some sense as a "struggle between the Treasury department and the republican interest," to use the words of Jefferson strategist John Beckley.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1792-united-states-presidential-election] In New York, the race for governor was fought along these lines.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The candidates were Chief Justice John Jay, a Hamiltonian, and incumbent George Clinton, the party's vice presidential nominee.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Although Washington had been considering retiring, both sides encouraged him to remain in office to bridge factional differences.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Washington was supported by practically all sides throughout his presidency and gained more popularity with the passage of the Bill of Rights.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1792-united-states-presidential-election] However, the Democratic-Republicans and the Federalists contested the vice-presidency, with incumbent John Adams as the Federalist nominee and George Clinton as the Democratic-Republican nominee.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Federalists attacked Clinton for his past association with the anti-Federalists.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Congress counted the electoral results on February 13, 1793, with John Adams opening and reading the votes in his role as President of the Senate.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Washington was re-elected unanimously, receiving one vote from each of the 132 participating electors.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Adams received votes from 77 electors and Clinton 50; the four electors from Kentucky voted for Thomas Jefferson, and one South Carolina elector voted for Aaron Burr.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The distribution of the electoral vote between the four runners-up showed a high degree of party discipline, with only two electors voting contrary to the majority in their state.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Adams received the support of New England, South Carolina, and the Mid-Atlantic states (excepting New York), while Clinton carried New York and most of the South.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Nine of the 15 states eligible to choose representatives to the electoral college did so by a vote of the state legislature; the remaining six employed some form of popular vote.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Of these, complete returns from Maryland, Massachusetts, New Hampshire, and Pennsylvania survive; surviving returns from Virginia are incomplete, and popular vote records from Kentucky are not known to exist.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Of the states with complete returns, only Pennsylvania saw real partisan competition; a Federalist electoral slate pledged to Washington and Adams was selected, although one elector voted for Washington and Clinton.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1792-united-states-presidential-election] At the time, party organizations were still in their infancy, and the partisan allegiance of the candidates was not always evident: it is therefore difficult to say whether the Pennsylvania vote for Clinton was an instance of a faithless elector, or an elector voting as pledged.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Elections in this period were vastly different from modern day presidential elections.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The actual presidential candidates were rarely mentioned on tickets and voters were voting for particular electors who were pledged to a particular candidate.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1792-united-states-presidential-election] There was sometimes confusion as to who the particular elector was actually pledged to.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Results are reported as the highest result for an elector for any given faction.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1792-united-states-presidential-election] For example, if three Federalist electors received 100, 50, and 25 votes, Federalist electors would be recorded as having 100 votes.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Confusion surrounding the way results are reported may lead to discrepancies between the sum of all state results and national results.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1792-united-states-presidential-election] In Massachusetts, the best performing elector candidate for the Eastern District, Thomas Rice, was not selected by the Massachusetts General Court to be an elector.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Rice was a Federalist and his returns have been included into the state total below instead of the second best performing elector candidate.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The totals for Kentucky, Pennsylvania, and Virginia appear to be incomplete.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1792-united-states-presidential-election] In several states candidates of unknown affiliation received votes.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The states chose 135 electors, out of whom 132 cast ballots.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1792-united-states-presidential-election] (Two electors from Maryland and one from Vermont were absent and did not vote.) As per the terms of the unamended constitution, each elector was permitted two votes for president, with a majority of "the whole number of electors appointed" necessary to elect a president.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Each of the participating electors cast one vote for Washington, who was elected president.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The electors were split on their second choice: Adams received 77 votes to Clinton's 50, enough to secure a second-place finish behind Washington and the vice presidency.
[src:thomas-jefferson/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The Constitution, in Article II, Section 1, provided that the state legislatures should decide the manner in which their Electors were chosen.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Jefferson was born into the Colony of Virginia's planter class.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] During the American Revolution, he represented Virginia in the Second Continental Congress, which unanimously adopted the Declaration of Independence.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Jefferson's advocacy for individual rights, including freedom of thought, speech, and religion, helped shape the ideological foundations of the revolution.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Jefferson served as the second governor of Virginia from 1779 to 1781.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Minister to France, where he served from 1785 to 1789.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] President George Washington then appointed Jefferson the nation's first secretary of state, where he served from 1790 to 1793.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] In 1792, Jefferson and political ally James Madison organized the Democratic-Republican Party to oppose the Federalist Party during the formation of the nation's First Party System.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Jefferson and Federalist John Adams became both personal friends and political rivals.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] In the 1796 U.S. presidential election between the two, Jefferson came in second, which made him Adams' vice president under the electoral laws of the time.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Four years later, in the 1800 presidential election, Jefferson again challenged Adams and won the presidency.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] When running for reelection in 1804, Jefferson overwhelmingly defeated the Federalists' Charles Cotesworth Pinckney of South Carolina.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] In his second presidential term, Jefferson was beset by difficulties at home, including the trial of his former vice president Aaron Burr.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] In 1807, Jefferson implemented the Embargo Act to defend the nation's industries from British threats to U.S. shipping, limit foreign trade, and stimulate the birth of the American manufacturing.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Jefferson is ranked among the upper tier of U.S. presidents both by scholars and in public opinion.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Presidential scholars and historians have praised Jefferson's advocacy of religious freedom and tolerance, his peaceful acquisition of the Louisiana Territory from France, and his leadership in supporting the Lewis and Clark Expedition.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] They acknowledge his lifelong ownership of large numbers of slaves, but offer varying interpretations of his views on and relationship with slavery.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Jefferson was born on April 13, 1743 (April 2, 1743, Old Style, Julian calendar), at the family's Shadwell Plantation in the Colony of Virginia, then one of the Thirteen Colonies of British America.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] His father, Peter Jefferson, was a planter and surveyor; his mother was Jane Randolph.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Peter Jefferson moved his family to Tuckahoe Plantation in 1745 following the death of William Randolph III, the plantation's owner and Jefferson's friend, who in his will had named Peter guardian of Randolph's children.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] The Jeffersons returned to Shadwell before October 1753.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Jefferson began his education together with the Randolph children at Tuckahoe under tutors.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Thomas' father Peter, who was self-taught and regretted not having a formal education, entered Thomas into an English school at age five.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] In 1752, at age nine, he attended a local school run by a Presbyterian minister and also began studying the natural world, which he grew to love.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] He studied Latin, Greek, and French, and began learning to ride horses.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Thomas read books from his father's modest library.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] He was taught from 1758 to 1760 by the Reverend James Maury near Gordonsville, Virginia, where he studied history, science, and the classics while boarding with Maury's family.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Jefferson came to know various Native Americans including Cherokee chief Ostenaco, who often stopped at Shadwell to visit on their way to Williamsburg to trade.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] In Williamsburg, the young Jefferson met and came to admire Patrick Henry.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Thomas's father died in 1757, and his estate was divided between his sons, Thomas and Randolph.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] John Harvie Sr. became 14-year-old Thomas' guardian.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Thomas inherited approximately 5,000 acres (7.8 sq mi; 20.2 km2), which included the land on which he later built Monticello in 1772.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] In 1761, at the age of seventeen, Jefferson entered the College of William & Mary in Williamsburg, where he studied mathematics and philosophy with William Small.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Under Small's tutelage, Jefferson encountered the ideas of British empiricists, including John Locke, Francis Bacon, and Isaac Newton.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Small also introduced Jefferson to George Wythe and Francis Fauquier.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Small, Wythe, and Fauquier recognized Jefferson as a man of exceptional ability and included him in their inner circle, where he became a regular member of their Friday dinner parties.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Jefferson later wrote that, while there, he "heard more common good sense, more rational & philosophical conversations than in all the rest of my life".
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] During his first year in college, Jefferson spent considerable time attending parties and dancing and was not very frugal with his expenditures; in his second year, regretting that he had squandered away time and money in his first year, he committed to studying fifteen hours a day.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] While at William & Mary, Jefferson became a member of the Flat Hat Club, the nation's oldest secret society, a small group whose members included St.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] George Tucker, Edmund Randolph, and James Innes.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Jefferson concluded his formal studies in April 1762.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] He read the law under Wythe's tutelage while working as a law clerk in his office.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Jefferson was well-read in a broad variety of subjects, including law, philosophy, history, natural law, natural religion, ethics, and several areas of science, including astronomy and agriculture.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Jefferson kept two commonplace books: from about age 15 to 30, he compiled a book of sayings and quotations, published in the 20th century as *Jefferson's Literary Commonplace Book*.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] During his years of legal study under Wythe, Jefferson began recording his notes on law, history, and philosophy, and continued to do so until the end of his life; his *Legal Commonplace Book* was also published in the 20th century.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] On July 20, 1765, Jefferson's sister Martha married his close friend and college companion Dabney Carr, which greatly pleased Jefferson.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] In October of that year, however, Jefferson's sister Jane unexpectedly died at age 25.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Her death plunged Jefferson into a months-long period of mourning that was spoken of amongst the family.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Jefferson treasured his books and amassed three sizable libraries in his lifetime.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] He began assembling his first library, which grew to 200 volumes, in his youth.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Wythe was so impressed with Jefferson that he later bequeathed his entire library to him.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] In 1770, however, Jefferson's first library was destroyed in a fire at his Shadwell home.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] His second library, which replenished the first, grew to nearly 6,500 volumes by 1814.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Jefferson organized his books into three broad categories of the human mind: memory, reason, and imagination.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] After British forces set the Library of Congress on fire in the Burning of Washington in 1814, Jefferson sold his second library to the U.S. government for $23,950, hoping to help jumpstart the Library of Congress's rebuilding.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Jefferson used a portion of the proceeds to pay off some of his large debt.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Jefferson soon resumed collecting his third personal library.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] In a letter to John Adams, Jefferson wrote, "I cannot live without books." By the time of Jefferson's death a decade later, his third and final library had grown to nearly 2,000 volumes.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] In 1767, Jefferson was granted admission to the Virginia bar, and lived with his mother at Shadwell.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Between 1769 and 1775, he represented Albemarle County in Virginia's House of Burgesses.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] While serving in the House of Burgesses, Jefferson pursued reforms to slavery, including writing and sponsoring legislation in 1769 to strip power from the royal governor and courts, instead providing masters of slaves with the discretion to emancipate them.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Jefferson persuaded his cousin Richard Bland to spearhead the legislation's passage, but it faced strong opposition in a state whose economy was largely agrarian.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] As a lawyer, Jefferson took on seven freedom-seeking enslaved people as clients and waived his fee for one he claimed should be freed before the minimum statutory age for emancipation.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Jefferson invoked natural law, arguing "everyone comes into the world with a right to his own person and using it at his own will ...
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] This is what is called personal liberty, and is given him by the author of nature, because it is necessary for his own sustenance." The judge cut him off and ruled against his client.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] As a consolation, Jefferson gave his client some money, which was conceivably used to aid his escape shortly thereafter.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Jefferson's underlying intellectual argument that all people were entitled by their creator to what he labeled a "natural right" to liberty is a theme that he later prominently incorporated into the Declaration of Independence.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] In 1767, Jefferson took on 68 cases for the General Court of Virginia and was counsel in three notable cases of that era, *Howell v.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] In 1774, Jefferson authored a resolution calling for a boycott of all British goods in protest of the British Parliament's passing of the Intolerable Acts.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Jefferson's resolution was later expanded into *A Summary View of the Rights of British America*, published that year in which he argued that people have the right to govern themselves.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] In 1768, Jefferson began constructing his primary residence, Monticello near present-day Charlottesville, Virginia.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Its Italian name means "Little Mountain" in English.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Monticello is located on a hilltop overlooking his 5,000-acre (20 km2; 7.8 mi2) plantation.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] He spent most of his adult life designing Monticello as an architect and was quoted as saying, "Architecture is my delight, and putting up, and pulling down, one of my favorite amusements." Construction was done mostly by local masons and carpenters, assisted by Jefferson's slaves.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] He moved into the South Pavilion in 1770.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Turning Monticello into a neoclassical masterpiece in the Palladian style became Jefferson's lifelong project.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] On January 1, 1772, Jefferson married his third cousin, Martha Wayles Skelton, a 23-year-old widow of Bathurst Skelton.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] She was a frequent hostess for Jefferson and managed the large household.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Historian Dumas Malone described the marriage as the happiest period of Jefferson's life.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Martha was a skilled pianist; Jefferson often accompanied her on the violin or cello.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] During their ten-year marriage, Martha bore six children: Martha "Patsy" (1772–1836); Jane Randolph (1774–1775); an unnamed son who lived for only a few weeks in 1777; Mary "Polly" (1778–1804); Lucy Elizabeth (1780–1781); and another Lucy Elizabeth (1782–1784).
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Only Martha and Mary survived to adulthood.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Martha's father, John Wayles, died in 1773, and the couple inherited 135 enslaved people, 11,000 acres (45 km2; 17 mi2), and the estate's debts.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] The debts took Jefferson years to satisfy, contributing to his financial problems.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Martha later suffered from ill health, including diabetes, and frequent childbirth weakened her.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] A few months after the birth of her last child, she died on September 6, 1782, with Jefferson at her bedside.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Shortly before her death, Martha made Jefferson promise never to marry again, telling him that she could not bear to have another mother raise her children.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Jefferson was grief-stricken by her death, relentlessly pacing back and forth for roughly three weeks, and finally emerging to take long rambling rides on secluded roads with his daughter, Martha, who said she was "a solitary witness to many a violent burst of grief".
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Jefferson was the primary author of the Declaration of Independence.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] At age 33, he was one of the youngest delegates to the Second Continental Congress, which convened in the colonial capital of Philadelphia following the Battles of Lexington and Concord, which launched the American Revolutionary War in 1775.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Delegates to the Congress overwhelmingly favored authoring, ratifying, and issuing a formal declaration of independence from Britain.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Jefferson was inspired by the Enlightenment ideals of the sanctity of the individual, and the writings of Locke and Montesquieu.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Jefferson sought out John Adams, a Continental Congress delegate from Massachusetts and an emerging leader in the Congress.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] They became close friends, and Adams supported Jefferson's appointment to the Committee of Five, which the Congress charged with authoring the Declaration: Adams, Jefferson, Benjamin Franklin, Robert R.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] The committee initially thought that Adams should write the document, but Adams persuaded the committee to choose Jefferson due to Jefferson being a Virginian, popular, and a good writer by Adams.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Jefferson consulted with his fellow committee members, but mostly wrote the Declaration of Independence in isolation between June 11 and 28, 1776.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Jefferson drew considerably on his proposed draft of the Virginia Constitution, George Mason's draft of the Virginia Declaration of Rights, and other sources.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Other committee members made some changes, and a final draft was presented to Congress on June 28, 1776.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Congress began debate over its contents on Monday, July 1, resulting in the removal of roughly a fourth of Jefferson's original draft.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Jefferson resented the changes, but he did not speak publicly about them.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] On July 4, 1776, the Congress voted unanimously to ratify the Declaration, and delegates signed it on August 2.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Jefferson and the other delegates knew they were committing high treason against the Crown, which was punishable by torture and death.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Following its ratification, the Declaration was released publicly.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Two days after its ratification, on July 6, *The Pennsylvania Evening Post*, was the first newspaper to publish it.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] On July 8 at noon, it was read publicly and simultaneously for the first time at three designated locations: Trenton, New Jersey; Easton, Pennsylvania; and Philadelphia.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Contemporary historians generally view the Declaration of Independence as one of the most significant and influential written documents in world history, and Jefferson's preamble is regarded as an enduring statement on individual and human rights.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Jefferson's phrase "all men are created equal" has been called "one of the best-known sentences in the English language".
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Harvard University history chairman David Armitage has written that, "No American document has had a greater global impact than the Declaration of Independence", and historian Joseph Ellis has written that the Declaration includes "the most potent and consequential words in American history".
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] At the start of the American Revolution, Colonel Jefferson was named commander of the Albemarle County Militia on September 26, 1775.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] He was then elected to the Virginia House of Delegates for Albemarle County in September 1776, when finalizing the state constitution was a priority.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] For nearly three years, Jefferson assisted with the constitution and was especially proud of his Bill for Establishing Religious Freedom, which prohibited state support of religious institutions or enforcement of religious doctrine.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] The bill failed to pass, as did his legislation to disestablish the Anglican Church, but both were later revived by James Madison.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] In 1778, Jefferson was given the task of revising the state's laws.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] He drafted 126 bills in three years, including laws to streamline the judicial system.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] He proposed statutes that provided for general education, which he considered the basis of "republican government".
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Jefferson also was concerned that Virginia's powerful landed gentry were becoming a hereditary aristocracy and took the lead in abolishing what he called "feudal and unnatural distinctions".
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] He targeted laws such as entail and primogeniture by which a deceased landowner's oldest son was vested with all land ownership and power.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Jefferson was elected governor for one-year terms in 1779 and 1780.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] He transferred the state capital from Williamsburg to Richmond, and introduced additional measures for public education, religious freedom, and inheritance.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] During General Benedict Arnold's 1781 invasion of Virginia, Jefferson escaped Richmond just ahead of the British forces, which razed the city.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] He sent emergency dispatches to Colonel Sampson Mathews and other commanders in an attempt to repel Arnold's efforts.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] When the British occupied Norfolk, Jefferson had caused patriots to burn and destroy it in 1776.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] General Charles Cornwallis that spring dispatched a cavalry force led by Banastre Tarleton to capture Jefferson and members of the Assembly at Monticello, but Jack Jouett of the Virginia militia thwarted the British plan.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Jefferson escaped to Poplar Forest, his plantation to the west.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] When the General Assembly reconvened in June 1781, it conducted an inquiry into Jefferson's actions which eventually concluded that Jefferson had acted with honor, but Jefferson was not reelected.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] In April of the same year, his daughter Lucy died at age one.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] A second daughter of that name was born the following year, but she died at age two.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] In 1782, Jefferson refused a partnership offer by North Carolina Governor Abner Nash, in a profiteering scheme involving the sale of confiscated Loyalist lands.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Unlike some Founders, Jefferson was content with his Monticello estate and the land he owned in the vicinity of Virginia's Shenandoah Valley.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Jefferson thought of Monticello as an intellectual gathering place for James Madison, James Monroe, and other friends.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Jefferson accused British-based merchants of unfairly depressing tobacco prices and forcing Virginia planters to take on unsustainable debt loads.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] In 1780, Jefferson received a letter of inquiry from French diplomat François Barbé-Marbois into the geography, history, and government of Virginia, as part of a study of the United States.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Jefferson organized his responses in a book, *Notes on the State of Virginia* (1785).
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] The book explores what constitutes a good society, using Virginia as an exemplar.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Jefferson included extensive data about the state's natural resources and economy and wrote at length about slavery and miscegenation; he articulated his belief that blacks and whites could not live together as free people in one society because of justified resentments of the enslaved.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] He also wrote of his views on the American Indians, equating them to European settlers.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Jefferson was appointed a Virginia delegate to the Congress of the Confederation organized following the peace treaty with Great Britain in 1783.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] He was a member of the committee setting foreign exchange rates and recommended an American currency based on the decimal system that was adopted.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] He advised the formation of the Committee of the States to fill the power vacuum when Congress was in recess.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] The committee met when Congress adjourned, but disagreements rendered it dysfunctional.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Jefferson sent a letter (revealed in 2025) to Virginia Governor Benjamin Harrison, dated December 31, 1783, in which he relates the wave of enthusiasm of Europeans for taking up arms against their leaders.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Jefferson was sharing the affirmation of his own promotion of the right to bear arms that brought about the American Revolution.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] The letter also conveys Jefferson's anxiety over the final ratification of the Treaty of Paris formally ending the revolutionary war.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Signed initially by the parties in September, the still-outstanding consent of two colonies was required in London (then a two-month journey) by the following March.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] The deadline was ultimately but barely met, with the required signatures made in mid-January.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] In the Congress's 1783–1784 session, Jefferson acted as chairman of committees to establish a viable system of government for the new Republic and to propose a policy for settlement of the western territories.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] He was the principal author of the Land Ordinance of 1784, whereby Virginia ceded to the national government the vast area that it claimed northwest of the Ohio River.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] He insisted that this territory should not be used as colonial territory by any of the thirteen states, but that it should be divided into sections that could become states.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] He plotted borders for nine new states in their initial stages and wrote an ordinance banning slavery in all the nation's territories.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Congress made extensive revisions and rejected the ban on slavery.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] The provisions banning slavery, known as the "Jefferson Proviso", were modified and implemented three years later in the Northwest Ordinance of 1787 and became the law for the entire Northwest Territory.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] On May 7, 1784, Jefferson was appointed by the Congress of the Confederation to join Benjamin Franklin and John Adams in Paris as Minister Plenipotentiary for Negotiating Treaties of Amity and Commerce with Great Britain and other countries.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] With his young daughter Patsy and two servants, he departed in July 1784, arriving in Paris the next month.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Jefferson had Patsy educated at Pentemont Abbey.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Less than a year later, he was assigned the additional duty of succeeding Franklin as Minister to France.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] French foreign minister Count de Vergennes commented, "You replace Monsieur Franklin, I hear." Jefferson replied, "I succeed.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] No man can replace him." During his five years in Paris, Jefferson played a leading role in shaping U.S. foreign policy.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] In 1786, he met and fell in love with Maria Cosway, a married 27-year-old Italian-English musician.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] She returned to Great Britain after six weeks, but she and Jefferson maintained a lifelong correspondence.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] During the summer of 1786, Jefferson arrived in London to meet with John Adams, who was then serving as the nation's first US Ambassador to Britain.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Adams had official access to George III and arranged a meeting between Jefferson and the king.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Jefferson later described the king's reception of the men as "ungracious".
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] According to Adams's grandson, George III turned his back on both in a gesture of public insult.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Jefferson sent for his youngest surviving child, nine-year-old Polly, in June 1787.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] She was accompanied by a young slave from Monticello, Sally Hemings.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Jefferson had taken her older brother, James Hemings, to Paris as part of his domestic staff and had him trained in French cuisine.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] According to Sally's son, Madison Hemings, 16-year-old Sally and Jefferson began a sexual relationship in Paris, where she became pregnant.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Madison indicated his mother agreed to return to the United States only after Jefferson promised to free her children when they came of age.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] While in France, Jefferson became a regular companion of the Marquis de Lafayette, a French hero of the American Revolution, and Jefferson used his influence with Lafayette to procure trade agreements with France.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] As the French Revolution began, Jefferson agreed to allow his Paris residence at Hôtel de Langeac to be used for meetings by Lafayette and other revolutionary leaders.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] He was in Paris during the storming of the Bastille on July 14, 1789, and he consulted with Lafayette as Lafayette drafted the Declaration of the Rights of Man and of the Citizen.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Jefferson often found his mail opened by postmasters, so he invented his own enciphering device, the "Wheel Cipher"; he wrote important communications in code for the rest of his career.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Unable to attend the 1787 Constitution Convention, Jefferson supported the Constitution but desired the addition of the promised Bill of Rights.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Jefferson left Paris for America in September 1789.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] He remained a firm supporter of the French Revolution while opposing its more violent elements.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Soon after returning from France, Jefferson accepted President Washington's invitation to serve as Secretary of State.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] After lengthy deadlock, the Compromise of 1790 was struck, permanently locating the capital on the Potomac River, and the federal government assumed the war debts of all original 13 states.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Jefferson opposed a national debt, preferring that each state retire its own, which contrasted with Hamilton's vision of the federal government consolidating state debts and establishing national credit and a national bank.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Jefferson strenuously opposed both policies and attempted to undermine Hamilton's agenda, which nearly led Washington to dismiss him from the cabinet.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Jefferson's goals were to decrease American dependence on British commerce and to expand commercial trade with France.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] He sought to weaken Spanish colonialism of the Trans-Appalachia and British control in the North, believing this would aid in the pacification of Native Americans.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Along with political protegé James Madison, then a U.S.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Representative, and author Philip Freneau, Jefferson co-founded the *National Gazette* in Philadelphia in 1791, which sought to counter the policies of the Federalist Party, which Hamilton was promoting through the *Gazette of the United States*, an influential Federalist newspaper.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] The *National Gazette* criticized the policies promoted by Hamilton, often in anonymous essays signed by the pen name *Brutus* at Jefferson's urging and written by Madison.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] In the spring of 1791, Jefferson was suffering from migraines and tiring of the infighting with Hamilton, so he and Madison departed for a vacation in Vermont.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] In May 1792, Jefferson's concern about emerging political rivalries in the young nation was escalating, and he wrote Washington, imploring him to run for reelection for a second term that year as a unifying influence.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] He urged the president to rally the citizenry to a party that would defend democracy against the corrupting influence of banks and financial-focused interests, which the Federalists were embracing and espousing.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Historians recognize Jefferson's letter to Washington as one of the first delineations of Democratic-Republican Party principles.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Jefferson, Madison, and other Democratic-Republican organizers favored states' rights and local control and opposed the federal concentration of power.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Hamilton, conversely, sought more power vested in the federal government.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Jefferson supported France against Britain when the two nations fought in 1793, though his arguments in Washington's Cabinet were undercut by French Revolutionary envoy Edmond-Charles Genêt's open scorn for Washington.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] In discussions with British Minister George Hammond, Jefferson tried in vain to persuade the British to vacate their posts in the Northwest and to compensate the U.S. for enslaved people freed by the British at the end of the Revolutionary War.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Jefferson also sought to return to private life, and resigned from the cabinet in December 1793; he may also have wanted to bolster his political influence from outside the administration.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] After the Washington administration negotiated the Jay Treaty with Britain in 1794, Jefferson saw a cause around which he could rally the Democratic-Republican Party.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] He organized national opposition to the treaty from Monticello.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] The treaty, designed by Hamilton, aimed to reduce tensions and increase trade.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Jefferson warned that it would increase British influence and subvert republicanism, calling it "the boldest act [Hamilton and Jay] ever ventured on to undermine the government".
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] The Treaty passed, but it expired in 1805 during Jefferson's presidential administration, and then President Jefferson did not renew it.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Jefferson continued his pro-France stance; during the violence of the Reign of Terror, he declined to disavow the revolution.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] "To back away from France would be to undermine the cause of republicanism in America", he wrote.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] In the presidential campaign of 1796, Jefferson lost the electoral college vote to Federalist John Adams 71–68.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] He did, however, receive the second-highest number of votes and, under the electoral laws at the time, was elected as vice president.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] As presiding officer of the United States Senate, Jefferson assumed a more passive role than his predecessor, John Adams.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] He allowed the Senate to freely conduct debates and confined his participation to procedural issues, which he called an "honorable and easy" role.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Jefferson previously studied parliamentary law and procedure for 40 years, making him qualified to serve as presiding officer.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] In 1800, he published his assembled notes on Senate procedure as *A Manual of Parliamentary Practice*.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] He cast only three tie-breaking votes in the Senate.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] In four confidential talks with French consul Joseph Létombe in the spring of 1797, Jefferson attacked Adams, predicting that his rival would only serve one term.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] He also encouraged France to invade England, and advised Létombe to stall any American envoys sent to Paris.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] This toughened the tone that the French government adopted toward the Adams administration.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] After Adams's initial peace envoys were rebuffed, Jefferson and his supporters lobbied for the release of papers related to the incident, called the XYZ Affair after the letters used to disguise the identities of the French officials involved.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] But the tactic backfired when it was revealed that French officials had demanded bribes, rallying public support against France.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] The U.S. began an undeclared naval war with France known as the Quasi-War.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] During the Adams presidency, the Federalists rebuilt the military, levied new taxes, and enacted the Alien and Sedition Acts.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Jefferson believed these laws were intended to suppress Democratic-Republicans, rather than prosecute enemy aliens, and considered them unconstitutional.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] To rally opposition, he and James Madison anonymously wrote the Kentucky and Virginia Resolutions, asserting that the federal government had no right to exercise powers not specifically delegated to it by the states.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] The resolutions followed the "interposition" approach of Madison, that states may shield their citizens from federal laws that they deem unconstitutional.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Jefferson advocated nullification, allowing states to entirely invalidate federal laws.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] He warned that, "unless arrested at the threshold", the Alien and Sedition Acts would "drive these states into revolution and blood".
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Biographer Ron Chernow contends that "the theoretical damage of the Kentucky and Virginia Resolutions was deep and lasting, and was a recipe for disunion", and contributed to the outbreak of the American Civil War and later events.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Washington was so appalled by the resolutions that he told Patrick Henry that, if "systematically and pertinaciously pursued", the resolutions would "dissolve the union or produce coercion".
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Jefferson had always admired Washington's leadership skills but felt that his Federalist party was leading the country in the wrong direction.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] He decided not to attend Washington's funeral in 1799 because of acute differences with him while serving as secretary of state.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Jefferson ran for president against John Adams again in 1800.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Adams' campaign was weakened by unpopular taxes and vicious Federalist infighting over his actions in the Quasi-War.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Democratic-Republicans pointed to the Alien and Sedition Acts and accused the Federalists of being secret pro-Britain monarchists.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Federalists, in turn, charged that Jefferson was a godless libertine beholden to the French.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] UCLA history professor Joyce Appleby described the 1800 presidential election as "one of the most acrimonious in the annals of American history".
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] The Democratic-Republicans ultimately won more electoral college votes, due in part to the electors that resulted from the addition of three-fifths of the South's slaves to the population calculation under the Three-Fifths Compromise.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Jefferson and his vice presidential candidate Aaron Burr unexpectedly received an equal total.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Because of the tie, the election was decided by the Federalist-dominated U.S.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Hamilton lobbied Federalist representatives on Jefferson's behalf, believing him a lesser political evil than Burr.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] On February 17, 1801, after thirty-six ballots, the House elected Jefferson president and Burr vice president.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] The win led to Democratic-Republican celebrations throughout the country.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Some of Jefferson's opponents argued that he owed his victory to the South's inflated number of electors.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Others alleged that Jefferson secured James Asheton Bayard's tie-breaking electoral vote by promising to retain various Federalist posts in the government.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] Jefferson disputed the allegation, and the historical record is inconclusive.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p01] The transition proceeded smoothly, marking a watershed in American history.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] Jefferson was sworn in as president by Chief Justice John Marshall at the new Capitol in Washington, D.C., on March 4, 1801.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] His inauguration was not attended by outgoing President Adams.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] In contrast to his two predecessors, Jefferson exhibited a dislike of formal etiquette.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] Plainly dressed, he chose to walk alongside friends to the Capitol from his nearby boardinghouse instead of arriving by carriage.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] His inaugural address struck a note of reconciliation and commitment to democratic ideology, declaring, "We have been called by different names brethren of the same principle.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] We are all Republicans, we are all Federalists." Ideologically, he stressed "equal and exact justice to all men", minority rights, and freedom of speech, religion, and press.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] He said that a free and republican government was "the strongest government on earth".
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] He nominated moderate Republicans to his cabinet: James Madison as secretary of state, Henry Dearborn as secretary of war, Levi Lincoln as attorney general, and Robert Smith as secretary of the navy.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] Widowed since 1782, Jefferson first relied on his two daughters to serve as his official hostesses.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] In late May 1801, he asked Dolley Madison, wife of his long-time friend James Madison, to be the permanent White House hostess.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] She was also in charge of the completion of the White House mansion.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] Dolley served as White House hostess for the rest of Jefferson's two terms and then for another eight years as First Lady while her husband was president.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] Jefferson's first challenge as president was shrinking the $83 million national debt.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] He began dismantling Hamilton's Federalist fiscal system with help from the secretary of the treasury, Albert Gallatin.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] Gallatin devised a plan to eliminate the national debt in sixteen years by extensive annual appropriations and reduction in taxes.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] The administration eliminated the whiskey excise and other taxes after closing "unnecessary offices" and cutting "useless establishments and expenses".
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] Jefferson believed that the First Bank of the United States represented a "most deadly hostility" to republican government.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] He wanted to dismantle the bank before its charter expired in 1811, but was dissuaded by Gallatin.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] Gallatin argued that the national bank was a useful financial institution and set out to expand its operations.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] Jefferson looked to other corners to address the growing national debt.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] He shrank the Navy, for example, deeming it unnecessary in peacetime, and incorporated a fleet of inexpensive gunboats intended only for local defense to avoid provocation against foreign powers.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] After two terms, he had lowered the national debt from $83 million to $57 million.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] Jefferson pardoned several of those imprisoned under the Alien and Sedition Acts.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] Congressional Republicans repealed the Judiciary Act of 1801, which removed nearly all of Adams's "midnight judges".
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] A subsequent appointment battle led to the Supreme Court's landmark decision in *Marbury v.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] Madison*, asserting judicial review over executive branch actions.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] Jefferson appointed three Supreme Court justices: William Johnson (1804), Henry Brockholst Livingston (1807), and Thomas Todd (1807).
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] Jefferson strongly felt the need for a national military university, producing an officer engineering corps for a national defense based on the advancement of the sciences, rather than having to rely on foreign sources.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] He signed the Military Peace Establishment Act on March 16, 1802, founding the United States Military Academy at West Point.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] The act documented a new set of laws and limits for the military.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] Jefferson was also hoping to bring reform to the Executive branch, replacing Federalists and active opponents throughout the officer corps to promote Republican values.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] Jefferson took great interest in the Library of Congress, which had been established in 1800.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] In 1802, Congress authorized Jefferson to name the first Librarian of Congress, and formed a committee to establish library regulations.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] Congress also granted both the president and vice president the right to use the library.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] American merchant ships had been protected from Barbary Coast pirates by the Royal Navy when the states were British colonies.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] After independence, however, pirates often captured U.S. merchant ships, pillaged cargoes, and enslaved or held crew members for ransom.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] Jefferson had opposed paying tribute to the Barbary States since 1785.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] Navy fleet under Commodore Richard Dale to make a show of force in the Mediterranean, the first American naval squadron to cross the Atlantic.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] Following the fleet's first engagement, he successfully asked Congress for a declaration of war.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] The "First Barbary War" was the first foreign war fought by the U.S.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] Pasha of Tripoli Yusuf Karamanli captured the USS *Philadelphia*, so Jefferson authorized William Eaton, the U.S.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] Consul to Tunis, to lead a force to restore the pasha's older brother to the throne.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] The American navy forced Tunis and Algiers into breaking their alliance with Tripoli.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] Jefferson ordered five separate naval bombardments of Tripoli, leading the pasha to sign a treaty that restored peace in the Mediterranean.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] Spain ceded ownership of the Louisiana territory in 1800 to France.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] Jefferson was concerned that Napoleon's interests in the vast territory would threaten the security of the continent and Mississippi River shipping.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] He wrote that the cession "works most sorely on the U.S.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] It completely reverses all the political relations of the U.S." In 1802, he instructed James Monroe and Robert R.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] Livingston to negotiate the purchase of New Orleans and adjacent coastal areas.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] In early 1803, Jefferson offered Napoleon nearly $10 million for 40,000 square miles (100,000 square kilometres) of tropical territory.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] Napoleon realized that French military control was impractical over such a vast remote territory, and he was in dire need of funds for his wars on the home front.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] In early April 1803, he unexpectedly made negotiators a counter-offer to sell 827,987 square miles (2,144,480 square kilometres) of French territory for $15 million (~$380 million in 2024), doubling the size of the United States.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] U.S. negotiators accepted the offer and signed the treaty on April 30, 1803.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] Word of the unexpected purchase did not reach Jefferson until July 3, 1803.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] He unknowingly acquired the most fertile tract of land of its size on Earth, making the new country self-sufficient in food and other resources.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] The sale also significantly curtailed European presence in North America, removing obstacles to U.S. westward expansion.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] Most thought that this was an exceptional opportunity, despite Republican reservations about the Constitutional authority of the federal government to acquire land.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] Jefferson initially thought that a Constitutional amendment was necessary to purchase and govern the new territory; but he later changed his mind, fearing that this would give cause to oppose the purchase, and urged a speedy debate and ratification.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] On October 20, 1803, the Senate ratified the purchase treaty by a vote of 24–7.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] Jefferson personally was humble about acquiring the Louisiana Territory, but he resented complainers who called the vast domain a "howling wilderness".
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] After the purchase, Jefferson preserved the region's Spanish legal code and instituted a gradual approach to integrating settlers into American democracy.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] He believed that a period of the federal rule would be necessary while Louisianans adjusted to their new nation.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] Historians have differed in their assessments regarding the constitutional implications of the sale, but they typically hail the Louisiana acquisition as a major accomplishment.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] Frederick Jackson Turner called the purchase the most formative event in American history.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] Jefferson anticipated further westward settlements due to the Louisiana Purchase and arranged for the exploration and mapping of the uncharted territory.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] He sought to establish a U.S. claim ahead of competing European interests and to find the rumored Northwest Passage.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] Jefferson and others were influenced by exploration accounts of Le Page du Pratz in Louisiana (1763) and James Cook in the Pacific (1784), and they persuaded Congress in 1804 to fund an expedition to explore and map the newly acquired territory to the Pacific Ocean.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] Jefferson appointed secretary Meriwether Lewis and acquaintance William Clark to lead the Corps of Discovery (1803–1806).
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] The expedition lasted from May 1804 to September 1806 and obtained a wealth of scientific and geographic knowledge, including knowledge of many Indian tribes.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] Jefferson organized three other western expeditions: the William Dunbar and George Hunter Expedition on the Ouachita River (1804–1805), the Thomas Freeman and Peter Custis Expedition (1806) on the Red River, and the Zebulon Pike Expedition (1806–1807) into the Rocky Mountains and the Southwest.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] All three produced valuable information about the American frontier.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] This interest also motivated Jefferson to meet the Prussian explorer Alexander von Humboldt several times in June 1804, inquiring into Humboldt's knowledge of New Spain's natural resources, economic prospects, and demographic development.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] Jefferson refuted the contemporary notion that Indians were inferior and maintained that they were equal in body and mind to people of European descent, although he believed them to be inferior in terms of culture and technology.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] As governor of Virginia during the Revolutionary War, Jefferson recommended moving the Cherokee and Shawnee tribes, who had allied with the British, to west of the Mississippi River.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] But when he took office as president, he quickly took measures to avert another major conflict, as American and Indian societies were in collision and the British were inciting Indian tribes from Canada.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] In Georgia, he stipulated that the state would release its legal claims for lands to its west in exchange for military support in expelling the Cherokee from Georgia.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] This facilitated his policy of western expansion, to "advance compactly as we multiply".
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] In keeping with his Enlightenment thinking, President Jefferson adopted an assimilation policy toward American Indians known as his "civilization program" which included securing peaceful U.S.–Indian treaty alliances and encouraging agriculture.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] Jefferson advocated that Indian tribes should make federal purchases by credit holding their lands as collateral.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] Various tribes accepted Jefferson's policies, including the Shawnees led by Black Hoof, the Muscogee, and the Cherokee.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] However, some Shawnees, led by Tecumseh, broke off from Black Hoof, and opposed Jefferson's assimilation policies.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] Historian Bernard Sheehan argues that Jefferson believed that assimilation was best for American Indians, and next-best was removal to the west; he felt that the worst outcome of the conflict would be their attacking the whites.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] Peterson argue that Jefferson's actual Indian policies did little to promote assimilation and were a pretext to seize lands.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] Jefferson was nominated for reelection by the Democratic-Republican Party, with George Clinton replacing Burr as his running mate.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] The Federalist Party ran Charles Cotesworth Pinckney of South Carolina, John Adams's vice presidential candidate in the 1800 election.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] The Jefferson-Clinton ticket won overwhelmingly in the electoral college vote, by 162 to 14, promoting their achievement of a strong economy, lower taxes, and the Louisiana Purchase.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] Jefferson and Madison backed resolutions to limit or ban British imports in retaliation for British seizures of American shipping.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] Also, in 1808, Jefferson was the first president to propose a broad federal plan to build roads and canals across several states, asking for $20 million, further alarming Randolph and believers of limited government.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] Jefferson's popularity suffered further in his second term as a result of his response to wars in Europe.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] Relations with Britain deteriorated, due partly to the antipathy between Jefferson and British diplomat Anthony Merry.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] After Napoleon's decisive victory at the Battle of Austerlitz in 1805, Napoleon became more aggressive in his negotiations with Jefferson and the U.S. over trading rights, which the U.S. proved unsuccessful in countering.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] Jefferson then led the enactment of the Embargo Act of 1807, directed at both France and Britain, which triggered economic chaos in the U.S. and was strongly criticized, leading Jefferson to abandon the policy a year later.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] During the American Revolution, colonial states abolished the international slave trade, but South Carolina reopened it.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] In his annual message of December 1806, Jefferson denounced the international slave trade as "violations of human rights" and called on the new Congress to immediately criminalize it.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] The following year, in 1807, Congress passed the Act Prohibiting Importation of Slaves, which Jefferson signed.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] The act established severe punishment against the international slave trade, although it did not address the issue domestically.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] In Haiti, Jefferson's neutrality allowed arms to flow to the slave independence movement during the Haitian Revolution, and Jefferson blocked attempts to assist Napoleon, who was defeated militarily in Haiti in 1803.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] But Jefferson's administration refused official recognition of Haiti during his second term, in deference to southern complaints about racial violence against slave holders.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] Recognition was not extended to Haiti until 1862.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] Following the 1801 electoral deadlock, Jefferson's relationship with his vice president, Aaron Burr, rapidly eroded.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] Jefferson suspected Burr of seeking the presidency for himself, while Burr was angered by Jefferson's refusal to appoint some of his supporters to federal office.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] Burr was dropped from the Democratic-Republican ticket in 1804 in favor of charismatic George Clinton.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] The same year, Burr was soundly defeated in his bid to be elected New York governor.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] During the campaign, Alexander Hamilton made publicly callous remarks regarding Burr's moral character.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] Burr challenged Hamilton to a duel, held on July 11, 1804.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] In the duel, Burr mortally wounded Hamilton, who died the following day.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] Burr was subsequently indicted for Hamilton's murder, causing him to flee to Georgia, even though he remained president of the U.S.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] Senate during Supreme Court Justice Samuel Chase's impeachment trial.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] Both indictments quietly died and Burr was not prosecuted.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] In August 1804, Burr contacted British Minister Anthony Merry offering to cede U.S. western territory in return for money and British ships.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] After leaving office in April 1805, Burr traveled west and conspired with Louisiana Territory governor James Wilkinson, beginning a large-scale recruitment for a military expedition.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] Burr discussed seizing control of Mexico or Spanish Florida, or forming a secessionist state in New Orleans or the Western U.S.; historians remain unclear as to his true goal.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] In the fall of 1806, Burr launched a military flotilla carrying about 60 men down the Ohio River.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] Wilkinson renounced the plot and reported Burr's expedition to Jefferson, who ordered Burr's arrest.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] On February 13, 1807, Burr was captured in Louisiana and sent to Virginia to be tried for treason.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] Burr's 1807 conspiracy trial became a national issue.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] Jefferson attempted to preemptively influence the verdict by telling Congress that Burr's guilt was "beyond question", but the case came before his longtime political foe, and distant cousin, John Marshall, who dismissed the treason charge.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] Burr's legal team subpoenaed Jefferson, but Jefferson refused to testify, making the first argument for executive privilege.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] Instead, Jefferson provided relevant legal documents.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] After a three-month trial, the jury found Burr not guilty, while Jefferson denounced his acquittal.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] Jefferson subsequently removed Wilkinson as territorial governor but retained him in the U.S. military.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] Banner criticized Jefferson for continuing to trust Wilkinson, a "faithless plotter".
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] Commanding General James Wilkinson was a holdover of the Washington and Adams administrations.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] In 1804, Wilkinson received 12,000 pesos from the Spanish for information on American boundary plans.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] Wilkinson also received advances on his salary and payments on claims submitted to Secretary of War Henry Dearborn.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] This damaging information apparently was unknown to Jefferson.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] In 1805, Jefferson trusted Wilkinson and appointed him Louisiana Territory governor, admiring Wilkinson's work ethic.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] In January 1806, Jefferson received information from Kentucky U.S.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] Attorney Joseph Davies that Wilkinson was on the Spanish payroll.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] Jefferson took no action against Wilkinson, since there was not then significant evidence against him.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] House of Representatives in December 1807 exonerated Wilkinson.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] In 1808, a military court looked into the allegations against Wilkinson but also found a lack of evidence.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] Jefferson retained Wilkinson in the U.S.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] Evidence found in Spanish archives in the 20th century proved Wilkinson was on the Spanish payroll.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] In the aftermath of the Louisiana Purchase, Jefferson attempted to annex West Florida from Spain.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] In his annual message to Congress, on December 3, 1805, Jefferson railed against Spain over Florida border depredations.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] A few days later Jefferson secretly requested a two-million-dollar expenditure to purchase Florida.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] Floor leader John Randolph opposed annexation, was upset over Jefferson's secrecy on the matter, and believed the money would end up going to Napoleon.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] The Two Million Dollar bill passed only after Jefferson successfully maneuvered to replace Randolph with Barnabas Bidwell as floor leader.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] This aroused suspicion of Jefferson and charges of undue executive influence over Congress.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] Jefferson signed the bill into law in February 1806.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] Six weeks later the law was made public.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] The two million dollars was to be given to France as payment, in turn, to put pressure on Spain to permit the annexation of Florida by the United States.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] France, however, refused the offer and Florida remained under Spanish control.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] The failed venture damaged Jefferson's reputation among his supporters.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] Starting in 1806, the Royal Navy began stopping American merchantmen to search for deserters from the British navy; approximately 6,000 sailors were impressed into the Royal Navy this way, leading to deep anger and resentment among the U.S. public.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] In 1806, Jefferson issued a call for a boycott of British goods; on April 18, Congress passed the Non-Importation Acts, but they were never enforced.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] Later that year, Jefferson asked James Monroe and William Pinkney to negotiate an end to foreign interference with American merchant shipping, though relations with Britain showed no signs of improving.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] The Monroe–Pinkney Treaty was finalized but lacked any provisions regarding the issue of impressment, and Jefferson refused to submit it to the Senate for ratification.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] The British warship HMS *Leopard* encountered the USS *Chesapeake* off the Virginia coast in June 1807; *Leopard* fired at *Chesapeake* after the latter refused to allow for a search for deserters before removing four deserters from the ship.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] Jefferson issued a proclamation banning British warships from U.S. waters.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] The USS *Revenge* was dispatched to demand an explanation from the British government, and Jefferson called for a special session of Congress in October to enact an embargo or alternatively to consider war.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] In December 1807, news arrived that Napoleon had extended the Berlin Decree, globally banning British imports.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] The Royal Navy, meanwhile continued to impress sailors from American merchant ships.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] However, Congress had no appetite to prepare the U.S. for war; Jefferson asked for and received the Embargo Act, an alternative that allowed the U.S. more time to build up defensive works, militias, and naval forces.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] Meacham argued that the Embargo Act was a projection of power that surpassed the Alien and Sedition Acts, and R.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] Bernstein said that Jefferson "was pursuing policies resembling those he had cited in 1776 as grounds for independence and revolution".
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] In November 1807, Jefferson, for several days, met with his cabinet to discuss the deteriorating foreign situation.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] Secretary of State James Madison supported the embargo, while Treasury Secretary Gallatin opposed it, due to its indefinite time frame and the risk to the policy of American neutrality.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] The U.S. economy suffered, criticism grew, and opponents began evading the embargo.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] Instead of retreating, Jefferson sent federal agents to secretly track down smugglers and violators.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] Three acts were passed in Congress during 1807 and 1808, called the *Supplementary*, the *Additional*, and the *Enforcement* acts.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] The government could not prevent American vessels from trading with the European belligerents once they had left American ports, although the embargo triggered a devastating decline in exports.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] In December 1807, Jefferson announced his intention not to seek a third term.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] He turned his attention increasingly to Monticello during the last year of his presidency, giving Madison and Gallatin almost total control of affairs.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] Shortly before leaving office in March 1809, Jefferson signed the repeal of the Embargo.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] In its place, the Non-Intercourse Act was passed, but it proved no more effective.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] The day before Madison was inaugurated as his successor, Jefferson said that he felt like "a prisoner, released from his chains".
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] After his presidency, Jefferson remained influential and continued to correspond with many of the country's leaders (including his two protégées, Madison and Monroe, who succeeded him as president); the Monroe Doctrine strongly resembles solicited advice that Jefferson gave to Monroe in 1823.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] Jefferson envisioned a university free of church influences where students could specialize in new areas not offered at other colleges.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] He believed that education engendered a stable society, which should provide publicly funded schools accessible based solely on ability.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] He initially proposed his university in a letter to Joseph Priestley in 1800 and, in 1819, founded the University of Virginia.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] He organized the state legislative campaign for its charter and, with the assistance of Edmund Bacon, purchased the location.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] He was the principal designer of the buildings, planned the university's curriculum, and served as the first rector upon its opening in 1825.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] Jefferson was a strong disciple of Greek and Roman architectural styles, which he believed to be most representative of American democracy.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] Each academic unit, called a pavilion, was designed with a two-story temple front, while the library "Rotunda" was modeled on the Roman Pantheon.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] Jefferson referred to the university's grounds as the "Academical Village", and he reflected his educational ideas in its layout.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] The ten pavilions included classrooms and faculty residences; they formed a quadrangle and were connected by colonnades, behind which stood the student rooms.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] Gardens and vegetable plots were placed behind the pavilions and were surrounded by serpentine walls, affirming the importance of the agrarian lifestyle.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] The university had a library rather than a church at its center, emphasizing its secular nature—controversial at the time.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] When Jefferson died in 1826, James Madison replaced him as rector.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] Jefferson bequeathed most of his reconstructed library of almost 2,000 volumes to the university.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] Only one other ex-president has founded a university; Millard Fillmore founded the University at Buffalo in 1846.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] Jefferson and John Adams became good friends in the first decades of their political careers, serving together in the Continental Congress in the 1770s and in Europe in the 1780s.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] The Federalist/Republican split of the 1790s divided them, however, and Adams felt betrayed by Jefferson's sponsorship of partisan attacks, such as those of James Callender.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] Jefferson was angered by Adams' appointment of "midnight judges".
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] The two men did not communicate directly for more than a decade after Jefferson succeeded Adams as president.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] A brief correspondence took place between Abigail Adams and Jefferson after Jefferson's daughter Polly died in 1804, in an attempt at reconciliation unknown to Adams.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] However, an exchange of letters resumed open hostilities between Adams and Jefferson.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] As early as 1809, Benjamin Rush began to prod the two through correspondence to re-establish contact.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] In 1812, Adams wrote a short New Year's greeting to Jefferson, prompted earlier by Rush, to which Jefferson warmly responded.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] This initial correspondence began what historian David McCullough calls "one of the most extraordinary correspondences in American history".
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] Over the next 14 years, Jefferson and Adams exchanged 158 letters discussing their political differences, justifying their respective roles in events, and debating the revolution's import to the world.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] When Adams died on July 4, 1826, the 50th anniversary of the Declaration of Independence, his last words were an acknowledgment of his longtime friend and rival.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] "Thomas Jefferson survives", Adams said, unaware that Jefferson had died a few hours earlier.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] In 1821, at the age of 77, Jefferson began writing his *Autobiography of Thomas Jefferson: 1743–1790*, in which he said he sought to "state some recollections of dates and facts concerning myself".
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] He focused on the struggles and achievements he experienced until July 29, 1790, where the narrative stopped short.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] He excluded his youth, emphasizing the revolutionary era.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] He related that his ancestors came from Wales to America in the early 17th century and settled in the western frontier of the Virginia colony, which influenced his zeal for individual and state rights.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] Jefferson described his father as uneducated, but with a "strong mind and sound judgement".
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] He also addressed his enrollment in the College of William & Mary and his election to the Continental Congress in Philadelphia in 1775.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] The work is primarily concerned with the Declaration and reforming the government of Virginia.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] He used notes, letters, and documents to tell many of the stories.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] He suggested that this history was so rich that his personal affairs were better overlooked, but he incorporated a self-analysis using the Declaration and other patriotism.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] Thomas Jefferson was a philhellene, lover of Greek culture, who sympathized with the Greek War of Independence.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] He has been described as the most influential of the Founding Fathers who supported the Greek cause, viewing it as similar to the American Revolution.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] By 1823, Jefferson was exchanging ideas with Greek scholar Adamantios Korais.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] Jefferson advised Korais on building the political system of Greece by using classical liberalism and examples from the American governmental system, ultimately prescribing a government akin to that of a U.S. state.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] He also suggested the application of a classical education system for the newly founded First Hellenic Republic.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] Jefferson's philosophical instructions were welcomed by the Greek people.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] Korais became one of the designers of the Greek constitution and urged his associates to study Jefferson's works and other literature from the American Revolution.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] In the summer of 1824, the Marquis de Lafayette accepted an invitation from President James Monroe to visit the country.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] Jefferson and Lafayette had not seen each other since 1789.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] After visits to New York, New England, and Washington, Lafayette arrived at Monticello on November 4.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] The next morning Jefferson, Lafayette, and James Madison attended a tour and banquet at the University of Virginia.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] Jefferson had someone else read a speech he had prepared for Lafayette, as his voice was weak and could not carry.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] After an 11-day visit, Lafayette bid Jefferson goodbye and departed Monticello.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] Jefferson's approximately $100,000 of debt weighed heavily on his mind in his final months, as it became increasingly clear that he would have little to leave to his heirs.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] In February 1826, he successfully applied to the General Assembly to hold a public lottery as a fundraiser.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] His health began to deteriorate in July 1825, due to a combination of rheumatism from arm and wrist injuries, and intestinal and urinary disorders.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] On July 3, overcome by fever, Jefferson declined an invitation to attend an anniversary celebration of the Declaration in Washington.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] During his last hours, he was accompanied by family members and friends.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] Jefferson died on July 4, 1826, at 12:50 p.m. at age 83, on the 50th anniversary of the adoption of the Declaration of Independence.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] In the moments prior to his death, Jefferson instructed his treating physician, "No, doctor, nothing more", refusing laudanum.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] But his final significant words were, "Is it the Fourth?" or "This is the Fourth".
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] When his predecessor, John Adams, died at approximately 6:20 pm that same day, his last words were "Thomas Jefferson survives", though Adams was unaware that Jefferson had died several hours before.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] The sitting president was Adams's son, John Quincy Adams, and he called the coincidence of their deaths on the nation's anniversary "visible and palpable remarks of Divine Favor".
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] Shortly after Jefferson died, attendants found a gold locket on a chain around his neck, containing a small faded blue ribbon around a lock of his wife Martha's hair.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] In his advanced years, Jefferson became increasingly concerned that people would understand the principles in the Declaration of Independence, and the people responsible for writing it, and he continually defended himself as its author.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] He considered the document one of his greatest life achievements, in addition to authoring the Statute of Virginia for Religious Freedom and founding the University of Virginia.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] Absent from his epitaph were his political roles, including his presidency.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] Jefferson died deeply in debt, and was unable to pass on his estate freely to his heirs.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] He gave instructions in his will for disposal of his assets, including the freeing of Sally Hemings's children; but his estate, possessions, and slaves were sold at public auctions starting in 1827.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p02] In 1831, Monticello was sold by Martha Jefferson Randolph and the other heirs.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] Jefferson subscribed to the political ideals expounded by John Locke, Francis Bacon, and Isaac Newton, whom he considered the three greatest men who ever lived.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] He was also influenced by the writings of Gibbon, Hume, Robertson, Bolingbroke, Montesquieu, and Voltaire.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] Jefferson thought that the independent yeoman and agrarian life were ideals of republican virtues.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] He distrusted cities and financiers, favored decentralized government power, and believed that the tyranny that had plagued the common man in Europe was due to corrupt political establishments and monarchies.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] He supported efforts to disestablish the Church of England, wrote the Virginia Statute for Religious Freedom, and he pressed for a wall of separation between church and state.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] The Republicans under Jefferson were strongly influenced by the 18th-century British Whig Party, which believed in limited government.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] His Democratic-Republican Party became dominant in early American politics, and his views became known as Jeffersonian democracy.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] Jefferson wrote letters and speeches prolifically; these show him to be well-read in the philosophical literature of his day and of antiquity.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] Nevertheless, some scholars do not take Jefferson seriously as a philosopher mainly because he did not produce a formal work on philosophy.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] Jefferson continued to attend to more theoretical questions of natural philosophy and subsequently left behind a rich philosophical legacy in the form of presidential messages, letters, and public papers.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] Jefferson described himself as an Epicurean and agreed with Epictetus' works.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] Jefferson knew Epicurean philosophy from original sources, but also mentioned Pierre Gassendi's *Syntagma philosophicum* as influencing his ideas on Epicureanism.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] According to Jefferson's philosophy, citizens have "certain inalienable rights" and "rightful liberty is unobstructed action according to our will, within limits drawn around us by the equal rights of others".
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] Initially, Jefferson favored restricted voting to those who could actually have the free exercise of their reason by escaping any corrupting dependence on others.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] He advocated enfranchising a majority of Virginians, seeking to expand suffrage to include "yeoman farmers" who owned their own land while excluding tenant farmers, city day laborers, vagrants, most American Indians, and women.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] He was convinced that individual liberties were the fruit of political equality, which was threatened by the arbitrary government.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] Excesses of democracy in his view were caused by institutional corruption rather than human nature.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] He was less suspicious of a working democracy than many contemporaries.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] As president, Jefferson feared that the federal system enacted by Washington and Adams had encouraged corrupting patronage and dependence.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] He tried to restore a balance between the state and federal governments more nearly reflecting the Articles of Confederation, seeking to reinforce state prerogatives where his party was in the majority.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] According to Stanford Scholar Jack Rakove, "[w]hen Jefferson wrote 'all men are created equal' in the preamble to the Declaration, he was not talking about individual equality.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] Historian Henry Wiencek has noted Jefferson included slaves when he penned "*all men are created equal*" in the Declaration.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] As early as 1774, Jefferson had supported ending domestic slavery, and making slaves citizens.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] Later, writing in *Notes* (1781), Jefferson supported gradual emancipation of slaves, to be sent away from the U.S. to an unspecified place.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] The former slaves would be replaced by white immigrant workers.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] In 1792, Jefferson calculated that he was making a 4 percent profit every year on the birth of black children.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] After this he wrote that slavery presented an investment strategy for the future.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] Historian Brion Davis writes that Jefferson's emancipation efforts virtually ceased.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] Jefferson was steeped in the Whig tradition of the oppressed majority set against a repeatedly unresponsive court party in the Parliament.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] He justified small outbreaks of rebellion as necessary to get monarchial regimes to amend oppressive measures compromising popular liberties.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] In a republican regime ruled by the majority, he acknowledged "it will often be exercised when wrong".
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] But "the remedy is to set them right as to facts, pardon and pacify them".
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] As Jefferson saw his party triumph in two terms of his presidency and launch into a third term under James Madison, his view of the U.S. as a continental republic and an "empire of liberty" grew more upbeat.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] On departing the presidency, he described America as "trusted with the destines of this solitary republic of the world, the only monument of human rights, and the sole depository of the sacred fire of freedom and self-government".
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] Jefferson was a supporter of American expansionism, writing in 1801 that "it is impossible not to look forward to distant times when our rapid multiplication will expand itself beyond those limits, and cover the whole northern, if not the southern continent".
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] Jefferson considered democracy to be the expression of society and promoted national self-determination, cultural uniformity, and education of all males of the commonwealth.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] He supported public education and a free press as essential components of a democratic nation.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] After resigning as secretary of state in 1793, Jefferson focused on the electoral bases of the Republicans and Federalists.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] The "Republican" classification for which he advocated included "the entire body of landholders" everywhere and "the body of laborers" without land.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] Republicans united behind Jefferson as vice president, with the election of 1796 expanding democracy nationwide at grassroots levels.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] Jefferson promoted Republican candidates for local offices.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] Beginning with Jefferson's electioneering for the "revolution of 1800", his political efforts were based on egalitarian appeals.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] In his later years, he referred to the 1800 election "as real a revolution in the principles of our government as that of '76 was in its form", one "not effected indeed by the sword ... but by the ... suffrage of the people".
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] Voter participation grew during Jefferson's presidency, increasing to "unimaginable levels" compared to the Federalist Era, with turnout of about 67,000 in 1800 rising to about 143,000 in 1804.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] At the onset of the American Revolution, Jefferson accepted William Blackstone's argument that property ownership would sufficiently empower voters' independent judgement, but he sought to further expand suffrage by land distribution to the poor.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] In the heat of the Revolutionary Era and afterward, several states expanded voter eligibility from landed gentry to all propertied male, tax-paying citizens with Jefferson's support.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] In retirement, he gradually became critical of his home state for violating "the principle of equal political rights"—the social right of universal male suffrage.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] He sought a "general suffrage" of all taxpayers and militia-men, and equal representation by population in the General Assembly to correct preferential treatment of the slave-holding regions.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] Baptized in his youth, Jefferson became a governing member of his local Episcopal Church in Charlottesville, which he later attended with his daughters.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] Jefferson, however, spurned Biblical views of Christianity.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] Influenced by Deist authors during his college years, Jefferson abandoned mainstream Christianity after his review of New Testament teachings.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] Jefferson has sometimes been portrayed as a follower of the liberal religious strand of Deism that values reason over revelation.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] Nonetheless, in 1803, Jefferson asserted, "I am Christian, in the only sense in which [Jesus] wished any one to be".
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] Later, influenced by prominent Unitarian theologist, Joseph Priestley, Jefferson selected New Testament passages of Jesus' teachings into a private work he called *The Life and Morals of Jesus of Nazareth*, known today as the *Jefferson Bible*, which was never published during his lifetime.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] Jefferson believed that Jesus' message had been obscured and corrupted by Paul the Apostle, the Gospel writers and Protestant reformers.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] Peterson states that Jefferson was a theist "whose God was the Creator of the universe ... all the evidences of nature testified to His perfection; and man could rely on the harmony and beneficence of His work".
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] In a letter to John Adams, Jefferson wrote that what he believed was genuinely Christ's, found in the Gospels, was "as easily distinguishable as diamonds in a dunghill".
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] By omitting miracles and the resurrection, Jefferson made the figure of Jesus more compatible with a worldview based on reason, and defined being a Christian as one who followed the simple teachings of Jesus.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] Jefferson was firmly anticlerical, writing in "every age, the priest has been hostile to liberty ... they have perverted the purest religion ever preached to man into mystery and jargon." The full letter to Horatio Spatford can be read at the National Archives.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] Jefferson once supported banning clergy from public office but later relented.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] In 1777, he drafted the Virginia Statute for Religious Freedom.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] Ratified in 1786, it made compelling attendance or contributions to any state-sanctioned religious establishment illegal and declared that men "shall be free to profess ... their opinions in matters of religion".
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] The Statute is one of only three accomplishments he chose for his epitaph.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] Early in 1802, Jefferson wrote to the Danbury Connecticut Baptist Association that "religion is a matter which lies solely between Man and his God".
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] He interpreted the First Amendment as having built "a wall of separation between Church and State".
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] The phrase 'Separation of Church and State' has been cited several times by the Supreme Court in its interpretation of the Establishment Clause.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] Jefferson donated to the American Bible Society, saying the Four Evangelists delivered a "pure and sublime system of morality" to humanity.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] He thought Americans would rationally create "Apiarian" religion, extracting the best traditions of every denomination.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] He contributed generously to several local denominations near Monticello.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] Acknowledging organized religion would always be factored into political life, he encouraged reason over supernatural revelation to make inquiries into religion.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] He believed in a creator god, an afterlife, and the sum of religion as loving God and neighbors.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] But he also controversially rejected fundamental Christian beliefs, denying the conventional Christian Trinity, Jesus's divinity as the Son of God and miracles, the Resurrection of Christ, atonement from sin, and original sin.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] Jefferson believed that original sin was a gross injustice.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] Jefferson's unorthodox religious beliefs became an important issue in the 1800 presidential election.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] As president, Jefferson countered the accusations by praising religion in his inaugural address and attending services at the Capitol.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] Jefferson broadly agreed with the Unitarian view on Christianity, believing in one creator god, but denying the Trinity and resurrection.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] Jefferson distrusted government banks and opposed public borrowing, which he thought created long-term debt, bred monopolies, and invited dangerous speculation as opposed to productive labor.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] In one letter to Madison, he argued each generation should curtail all debt within 19 years, and not impose a long-term debt on subsequent generations.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] In 1791, President Washington asked Jefferson, then secretary of state, and Hamilton, the secretary of the treasury, if the Congress had the authority to create a national bank.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] While Hamilton believed so, Jefferson and Madison thought a national bank would ignore the needs of individuals and farmers, and would violate the Tenth Amendment by assuming powers not granted to the federal government by the states.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] Hamilton successfully argued that the implied powers given to the federal government in the Constitution supported the creation of a national bank, among other federal actions.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] Jefferson used agrarian resistance to banks and speculators as the first defining principle of an opposition party, recruiting candidates for Congress on the issue as early as 1792.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] As president, Jefferson was persuaded by Secretary of the Treasury Albert Gallatin to leave the bank intact but sought to restrain its influence.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] Scholars give radically differing interpretations on Jefferson's views and relationship with slavery.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] Jefferson lived in a planter economy largely dependent upon slavery, and as a wealthy landholder, used slave labor for his household, plantation, and workshops.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] He first recorded his slaveholding in 1774, when he counted 41 enslaved people.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] Over his lifetime he enslaved about 600 people; he inherited about 175 people while most of the remainder were people born on his plantations.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] Jefferson purchased some slaves in order to reunite their families.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] He sold approximately 110 people for economic reasons, primarily slaves from his outlying farms.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] In 1784, when the number of people he enslaved likely was approximately 200, he began to divest himself of many slaves, and by 1794 he had divested himself of 161 individuals.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] Approximately 100 slaves lived at Monticello at any given time.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] In 1817, the plantation recorded its largest slave population of 140 individuals.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] Jefferson once said, "My first wish is that the labourers may be well treated".
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] Jefferson did not work his slaves on Sundays and Christmas and he allowed them more personal time during the winter months.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] Some scholars doubt Jefferson's benevolence, noting cases of excessive slave whippings in his absence.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] His nail factory was staffed only by enslaved children.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] Many of the enslaved boys became tradesmen.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] Burwell Colbert, who started his working life as a child in Monticello's Nailery, was later promoted to the supervisory position of butler.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] Jefferson felt slavery was harmful to both slave and master but had reservations about releasing slaves from captivity, and advocated for gradual emancipation.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] In 1779, he proposed gradual voluntary training and resettlement to the Virginia legislature, and three years later drafted legislation allowing slaveholders to free their own slaves.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] In his draft of the Declaration of Independence, he included a section, stricken by other Southern delegates, criticizing King George III for supposedly forcing slavery onto the colonies.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] In 1784, Jefferson proposed the abolition of slavery in all western U.S. territories, limiting slave importation to 15 years.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] Congress, however, failed to pass his proposal by one vote.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] In 1787, Congress passed the Northwest Ordinance, a partial victory for Jefferson that terminated slavery in the Northwest Territory.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] Jefferson freed his slave Robert Hemings in 1794 and he freed his cook slave James Hemings in 1796.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] Jefferson freed his runaway slave Harriet Hemings in 1822.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] Upon his death in 1826, Jefferson freed five male Hemings slaves in his will.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] During his presidency, Jefferson allowed the diffusion of slavery into the Louisiana Territory hoping to prevent slave uprisings in Virginia and to prevent South Carolina secession.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] In 1804, in a compromise, Jefferson and Congress banned domestic slave trafficking for one year into the Louisiana Territory.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] In 1806 he officially called for anti-slavery legislation terminating the import or export of slaves.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] In 1819, Jefferson strongly opposed a Missouri statehood application amendment, which banned domestic slave importation and freed slaves at the age of 25 on grounds that it would destroy the union.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] In *Notes on the State of Virginia*, he created controversy by calling slavery a moral evil for which the nation would ultimately have to account to God.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] Jefferson wrote of his "suspicion" that Black people were mentally and physically inferior to Whites, but argued that they nonetheless had innate human rights.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] He therefore supported colonization plans that would transport freed slaves to another country, such as Liberia or Sierra Leone, though he recognized the impracticability of such proposals.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] During his presidency, Jefferson was for the most part publicly silent on the issue of slavery and emancipation, as the Congressional debate over slavery and its extension caused a dangerous north–south rift among the states, with talk of a northern confederacy in New England.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] The violent attacks on white slave owners during the Haitian Revolution due to injustices under slavery supported Jefferson's fears of a race war, increasing his reservations about promoting emancipation.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] After numerous attempts and failures to bring about emancipation, Jefferson wrote privately in an 1805 letter to William A.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] Claims that Jefferson fathered children with his slave Sally Hemings after his wife's death have been debated since 1802.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] Callender, after being denied a position as postmaster, alleged Jefferson had taken Hemings as a concubine and fathered several children with her.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] In 1998, a panel of researchers conducted a Y-DNA study of living descendants of Jefferson's uncle, Field, and of a descendant of Hemings's son, Eston Hemings.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] The results showed a match with the male Jefferson line.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] Subsequently, the Thomas Jefferson Foundation (TJF) formed a nine-member research team of historians to assess the matter.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] The TJF report concluded that "the DNA study ... indicates a high probability that Thomas Jefferson fathered Eston Hemings".
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] The TJF also concluded that Jefferson likely fathered all of Hemings's children listed at Monticello.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] In July 2017, the TJF announced that archeological excavations at Monticello had revealed what they believe to have been Sally Hemings's quarters, adjacent to Jefferson's bedroom.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] Since the results of the DNA tests were made public, the consensus among most historians has been that Jefferson had a sexual relationship with Sally Hemings and that he was the father of her son Eston Hemings.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] A minority of scholars maintain the evidence is insufficient to prove Jefferson's paternity conclusively.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] Based on DNA and other evidence, they note the possibility that additional Jefferson males, including his brother Randolph Jefferson and any one of Randolph's four sons, or his cousin, could have fathered Sally Hemings's children.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] After Jefferson's death in 1826, although not formally manumitted, Sally Hemings was allowed by Jefferson's daughter Martha to live in Charlottesville as a free woman with her two sons until her death in 1835.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] The Monticello Association refused to allow Sally Hemings' descendants the right of burial at Monticello.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] Jefferson was a farmer, obsessed with new crops, soil conditions, garden designs, and scientific agricultural techniques.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] His main cash crop was tobacco, but its price was usually low and it was rarely profitable.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] He tried to achieve self-sufficiency with wheat, vegetables, flax, corn, hogs, sheep, poultry, and cattle, but he lived perpetually beyond his means and was always in debt.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] Jefferson also planted two vineyards at Monticello and hoped to grow *Vitis vinifera,* the European wine grape species, to make wine, but the crop failed.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] His efforts were nonetheless an important contribution to the development of American viticulture.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] Jefferson mastered architecture through self-study.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] His primary authority was Andrea Palladio's 1570 *The Four Books of Architecture*.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] Jefferson helped popularize the Neo-Palladian style in the United States, utilizing designs for the Virginia State Capitol, the University of Virginia, Monticello, and others.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] In archaeology in 1784, Jefferson, using the trench method, started excavating a Monacan burial mound in Virginia.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] His excavations were prompted by him noticing local Native Americans visiting the site and the "Moundbuilders" question.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] His methods allowed him to witness the stratigraphic layout, the various human remains and other artifacts inside the mound.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] The evidence present at the site led him to admit that he saw no reason why the ancestors of the present-day Native Americans could not have raised those mounds.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] He was interested in birds and wine, and was a noted gourmet.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] As a naturalist, he was fascinated by the Natural Bridge geological formation, and in 1774 successfully acquired the Bridge by a grant from George III.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] As an advocate of Enlightenment ideals, Jefferson studied many aspects of the natural sciences and frequently corresponded, and even hosted on multiple occasions, with Prussian explorer, Alexander von Humboldt.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] Jefferson was a member of the American Philosophical Society for 35 years, beginning in 1780.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] Through the society he advanced the sciences and Enlightenment ideals, emphasizing that knowledge of science reinforced and extended freedom.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] His *Notes on the State of Virginia* was written in part as a contribution to the society.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] He became the society's third president on March 3, 1797, a few months after he was elected Vice President of the United States.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] On March 10, 1797, Jefferson gave a lecture, later published as a paper in 1799, which reported on the skeletal remains of an extinct large sloth, which he named *Megalonyx*, unearthed by saltpeter workers from a cave in what is now Monroe County, West Virginia.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] Jefferson is considered to be a pioneer of scientific paleontology research in North America.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] Jefferson served as APS president for the next eighteen years, including through both terms of his presidency.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] He introduced Meriwether Lewis to the society, where various scientists tutored him in preparation for the Lewis and Clark Expedition.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] He resigned on January 20, 1815, but remained active through correspondence.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] Jefferson had a lifelong interest in linguistics, and could speak, read, and write in a number of languages, including French, Greek, Italian, and German.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] In his early years, he excelled in classical languages.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] Jefferson later came to regard Greek as the "perfect language" as expressed in its laws and philosophy.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] While attending the College of William & Mary, he taught himself Italian.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] Here Jefferson first became familiar with the Anglo-Saxon language, studying it in a linguistic and philosophical capacity.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] He owned 17 volumes of Anglo-Saxon texts and grammar and later wrote an essay on the Anglo-Saxon language.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] Jefferson claimed to have taught himself Spanish during his nineteen-day journey to France, using only a grammar guide and a copy of *Don Quixote*.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] Linguistics played a significant role in how Jefferson modeled and expressed political and philosophical ideas.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] He believed that the study of ancient languages was essential in understanding the roots of modern language.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] Jefferson criticized language purists and supported the introduction of neologisms to English, foreseeing the emergence of "an American dialect".
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] He described the Académie Française, a body designated to regulate the French language, as an "endeavor to arrest the progress of their language".
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] He collected and understood a number of Native American vocabularies and instructed Lewis and Clark to record and collect various indigenous languages during their Expedition.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] When Jefferson moved from Washington after his presidency, he took 50 Native American vocabulary lists back to Monticello along with the rest of his possessions.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] Somewhere along the journey, a thief stole the heavy chest, thinking it was full of valuables, but its contents were dumped into the James River when the thief discovered it was only filled with papers.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] Thirty years of collecting were lost, with only a few fragments rescued from the muddy banks of the river.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] Jefferson was not an outstanding orator and preferred to communicate through writing or remain silent if possible.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] Jefferson invented many small practical devices and improved contemporary inventions, including a revolving book-stand and a "Great Clock" powered by the gravitational pull on cannonballs.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] He improved the pedometer, the polygraph (a device for duplicating writing), and the moldboard plow, an idea he never patented and gave to posterity.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] Jefferson can also be credited as the creator of the swivel chair, the first of which he created and used to write much of the Declaration of Independence.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] He first opposed patents but later supported them.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] From 1790 to 1793, as Secretary of State, he was the *ex officio* head of the three-person patent review board.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] He drafted reforms of US patent law which led to him being relieved of this duty in 1793, and also drastically changed the patent system.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] As Minister to France, Jefferson was impressed by the military standardization program known as the *Système Gribeauval*, and initiated a program as president to develop interchangeable parts for firearms.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] For his inventiveness and ingenuity, Jefferson was awarded an honorary Doctor of Law degree from Harvard University in 1787.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] Jefferson is seen as an icon of individual liberty, democracy, and republicanism, hailed as the author of the Declaration of Independence, an architect of the American Revolution, and a renaissance man who promoted science and scholarship.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] The participatory democracy and expanded suffrage he championed defined his era and became a standard for later generations.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] Jon Meacham opined that Jefferson was the most influential figure of the democratic republic in its first half-century, succeeded by presidential adherents James Madison, James Monroe, Andrew Jackson, and Martin Van Buren.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] A Siena Research Institute poll of presidential scholars, which began in 1982, has consistently ranked Jefferson as one of the five best U.S. presidents, and a 2015 Brookings Institution poll of American Political Science Association members ranked him as the fifth-greatest president.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] Jefferson has been memorialized with buildings, sculptures, postage, and currency.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] In the 1920s, Jefferson, together with George Washington, Theodore Roosevelt, and Abraham Lincoln, was chosen by sculptor Gutzon Borglum and approved by President Calvin Coolidge to be depicted in a stone national memorial at Mount Rushmore in the Black Hills in South Dakota.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] The Jefferson Memorial was dedicated in Washington, D.C., in 1943, on the 200th anniversary of Jefferson's birth.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] The interior of the memorial includes a 19-foot (6 m) statue of Jefferson by Rudulph Evans and engravings of passages from Jefferson's writings.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] Most prominent among these passages are the words inscribed around the Jefferson Memorial: "I have sworn upon the altar of God eternal hostility against every form of tyranny over the mind of man", a quote from Jefferson's September 23, 1800, letter to Benjamin Rush.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] Several species have been named after Jefferson, both during and after his life.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] Most notable is from a fossil taxon of ground sloths, †*Megalonyx*.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] Jefferson himself had defined the genus in 1799 without naming a species.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] The species of the type fossil would be classified †*M. jeffersonii* (Jefferson's ground sloth) in honor of Jefferson by Anselme Gaëtan Desmarest in 1822.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] The flower genus *Jeffersonia* (Barton, 1793) and Virginia's state fossil †*Chesapecten jeffersonius* (Say, 1824) were also named after Jefferson during his lifetime.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] After his death, †*Carabus jeffersoni* (Scudder, 1900); †*Mammuthus jeffersonii* (Osborn, 1922); *Brachypanorpa jeffersoni* (Byers, 1976); †*Boreogomphodon jeffersoni* (Sues & Olsen, 1990); and *Coiba jeffersoni* (Kula, 2009) would be named in his honor.
[src:thomas-jefferson/thomas-jefferson-p03] The statue was taken down the next month.
